@* Searching for module names.
The |mod_lookup| procedure finds the module name |mod_text(1..l)| in the
search tree, after inserting it if necessary, and returns a pointer to
where it was found.
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype long_name_index is INTEGER range 0..longest_name;
@!mod_text:array (long_name_index) of ASCII_code; {name being sought for}
 
@ According to the rules of \.{AWEB}, no module name
should be a proper prefix of another, so a ``clean'' comparison should
occur between any two names. The result of |mod_lookup| is 0 if this
prefix condition is violated. An error message is printed when such violations
are detected during phase two of \.{AWEAVE}.
 
@<Types...@>=
type compare is (@!less,@!equal,@!greater,@!prefix,@!extension);
 
@ @<Specification of procedures visible from |searching|@>=
  function mod_lookup(l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer;

@ @<Procedures in |searching|@>=
function @!mod_lookup(@!l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer is {finds module name}
@!c:compare:=greater; {comparison between two names}
@!j:long_name_index; {index into |mod_text|}
@!k:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
@!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
@!p:name_pointer:=root; {current node of the search tree}
@!q:name_pointer:=0; {father of node |p|}
begin
while p/=0 loop
  @<Set variable |c| to the result of comparing the given name to
    name |p|@>;
  q:=p;
  if c=less then p:=llink(q);
  elsif c=greater then p:=rlink(q);
  else goto found;
  end if;
  end loop;
@<Enter a new module name into the tree@>;
<<found>> if c/=equal then
  err_print("! Incompatible section names"); p:=0;
@.Incompatible module names@>
  end if;
return p;
end mod_lookup;
 
@ @<Enter a new module name...@>=
w:=name_ptr mod ww; k:=byte_ptr(w);
if k+l>max_bytes then overflow("byte memory");
end if;
if name_ptr>max_names-ww then overflow("name");
end if;
p:=name_ptr;
if c=less then llink(q):=p; else rlink(q):=p;
end if;
llink(p):=0; rlink(p):=0; c:=equal;
for m in 1..l loop byte_mem(w,k+m-1):=mod_text(m);
end loop;
byte_ptr(w):=k+l; byte_start(name_ptr+ww):=k+l; incr(name_ptr)@;
 
@ @<Set variable |c|...@>=
k:=byte_start(p); w:=p mod ww; c:=equal; j:=1;
while (k<byte_start(p+ww)) and (j<=l) and (mod_text(j)=byte_mem(w,k)) loop
  incr(k); incr(j);
  end loop;
if k=byte_start(p+ww) then
  if j>l then c:=equal;
  else c:=extension;
  end if;
elsif j>l then c:=prefix;
elsif mod_text(j)<byte_mem(w,k) then c:=less;
else c:=greater;
end if@;
 
@ The |prefix_lookup| procedure is supposed to find exactly one module
name that has |mod_text(1..l)| as a prefix. Actually the algorithm silently
accepts also the situation that some module name is a prefix of
|mod_text(1..l)|, because the user who painstakingly typed in more than
necessary probably doesn't want to be told about the wasted effort.
 
@<Specification of procedures visible from |searching|@>=
  function prefix_lookup(l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer;

@ @<Procedures in |searching|@>=
function @!prefix_lookup(@!l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer is {finds name extension}
@!c:compare; {comparison between two names}
@!count:name_index:=0; {the number of hits}
@!j:long_name_index; {index into |mod_text|}
@!k:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
@!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
@!p:name_pointer:=root; {current node of the search tree}
@!q:name_pointer:=0; {another place to resume the search after one branch is done}
@!r:name_pointer:=0; {extension found}
begin
while p/=0 loop
  @<Set variable |c|...@>;
  if c=less then p:=llink(p);
  elsif c=greater then p:=rlink(p);
  else  r:=p; incr(count); q:=rlink(p); p:=llink(p);
    end if;
  if p=0 then
    p:=q; q:=0;
    end if;
  end loop;
if count/=1 then
  if count=0 then err_print("! Name does not match");
@.Name does not match@>
  else err_print("! Ambiguous prefix");
@.Ambiguous prefix@>
  end if;
end if;
return r; {the result will be 0 if there was no match}
end prefix_lookup;
 
@* Lexical scanning.
Let us now consider the subroutines that read the \.{AWEB} source file
and break it into meaningful units. There are four such procedures:
One simply skips to the next `\.{@@\ }' or `\.{@@*}' that begins a
module; another passes over the \TeX\ text at the beginning of a
module; the third passes over the \TeX\ text in a \ADA\ comment;
and the last, which is the most interesting, gets the next token of
a \ADA\ text.
@.\AT!\ @>
@.\AT!*@>

@ But first we need to consider the low-level routine |get_line|
that takes care of merging |change_file| into |aweb_file|. The |get_line|
procedure also updates the line numbers for error messages.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!line:INTEGER; {the number of the current line in the current file}
@!other_line:INTEGER; {the number of the current line in the input file that
  is not currently being read}
@!temp_line:INTEGER; {used when interchanging |line| with |other_line|}
@!limit:buffer_index; {the last character position occupied in
                                    the buffer}
@!loc:buffer_index; {the next character position to be read from
                                  the buffer}
@!input_has_ended: BOOLEAN; {if |TRUE|, there is no more input}
@!changing: BOOLEAN; {if |TRUE|, the current line is from |change_file|}
 
@ As we change |changing| from |TRUE| to |FALSE| and back again, we must
remember to swap the values of |line| and |other_line| so that the 
|err_print| routine will be sure to report the correct line number.
 
@d change_changing==
  changing := not changing;
  temp_line:=other_line; other_line:=line; line:=temp_line@;
    {|line @t$\null\BA\null$@> other_line|}
 
@ When |changing| is |FALSE|, the next line of |change_file| is kept in
|change_buffer(0..change_limit)|, for purposes of comparison with the next
line of |aweb_file|. After the change file has been completely input, we
set |change_limit:=0|, so that no further matches will be made.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!change_buffer:buffer_type(buffer_index);
@!change_limit:buffer_index; {the last position occupied in |change_buffer|}
 
@ Here's a simple function that checks if the two buffers are different.
 
@<Procedures in |lex...@>=
function @!lines_dont_match return BOOLEAN is
begin 
if change_limit/=limit then return TRUE;
end if;
if (limit>0) and then change_buffer(0..limit-1)/=buffer(0..limit-1) then 
   return TRUE;
end if;
return FALSE;
end lines_dont_match;
 
@ Procedure |prime_the_change_buffer| sets |change_buffer| in preparation
for the next matching operation. Since blank lines in the change file are
not used for matching, we have |(change_limit=0)and not changing| if and
only if the change file is exhausted. This procedure is called only
when |changing| is true; hence error messages will be reported correctly.
 
@<Procedures in |lex...@>=
procedure @!prime_the_change_buffer is
begin change_limit:=0; {this value will be used if the change file ends}
@<Skip over comment lines in the change file; |return@;| if end of file@>;
@<Skip to the next nonblank line; |return@;| if end of file@>;
@<Move |buffer| and |limit| to |change_buffer| and |change_limit|@>;
end prime_the_change_buffer;
 
@ While looking for a line that begins with \.{@@x} in the change file,
we allow lines that begin with \.{@@}, as long as they don't begin with
\.{@@y} or \.{@@z} (which would probably indicate that the change file is
fouled up).
@.\AT!x@> 
@.\AT!y@> 
@.\AT!z@> 
 
@<Skip over comment lines in the change file...@>=
loop  incr(line);
  if not input_ln(change_file) then return; 
  elsif limit<2 then goto continue; 
  elsif buffer(0)/=@'@@' then goto continue; 
  elsif buffer(1) in @'X'..@'Z' then
    buffer(1):=buffer(1)+8#40#; {lowercasify}
  end if;
  exit when buffer(1)=@'x';
  if buffer(1) in @'y'..@'z' then
    loc:=2; err_print("! Where is the matching @@x?");
@.Where is the match...@>
    end if;
<<continue>> null; 
end loop@;
 
@ Here we are looking at lines following the \.{@@x}.
@.\AT!x@> 
 
@<Skip to the next nonblank line...@>=
loop incr(line);
  if not input_ln(change_file) then
    err_print("! Change file ended after @@x");@/
@.Change file ended...@>
    return;
    end if;
exit when limit>0;
end loop@; 
   
@ @<Move |buffer| and |limit| to |change_buffer| and |change_limit|@>=
change_limit:=limit;
if limit>0 then change_buffer(0..limit-1):=buffer(0..limit-1);
end if@;
 
@ The following procedure is used to see if the next change entry should
go into effect; it is called only when |changing| is false.
The idea is to test whether or not the current
contents of |buffer| matches the current contents of |change_buffer|.
If not, there's nothing more to do; but if so, a change is called for:
All of the text down to the \.{@@y} is supposed to match. An error
message is issued if any discrepancy is found. Then the procedure
prepares to read the next line from |change_file|.
@.\AT!y@> 
 
@<Procedures in |lex...@>=
procedure @!check_change is {switches to |change_file| if the buffers match}
@!n:INTEGER:=0; {the number of discrepancies found}
begin if lines_dont_match then return; end if;
loop  change_changing; {now it's |TRUE|}
  incr(line);
  if not input_ln(change_file) then
    err_print("! Change file ended before @@y");@/
@.Change file ended...@>
    change_limit:=0;  change_changing; {|FALSE| again}
    return;
    end if;
  @<If the current line starts with \.{@@y},
    report any discrepancies and |return@;|@>;
  @<Move |buffer| and |limit|...@>;
  change_changing; {now it's |FALSE|}
  incr(line);
  if not input_ln(aweb_file) then
    err_print("! AWEB file ended during a change");@/
@.AWEB file ended...@>
    input_has_ended:=TRUE; return;
    end if;
  if lines_dont_match then incr(n); end if;
  end loop;
end check_change;
 
@ @<If the current line starts with \.{@@y}...@>=
@.\AT!y@> 
if (limit>1) and then buffer(0)=@'@@' then
  if buffer(1) in @'X'..@'Z' then
    buffer(1):=buffer(1)+8#40#; {lowercasify}
  end if;
  if (buffer(1)=@'x')or(buffer(1)=@'z') then
    loc:=2; err_print("! Where is the matching @@y?");
@.Where is the match...@>
  elsif buffer(1)=@'y' then
    if n>0 then
      loc:=2; new_ln;
      print("! Hmm... ");
      print_int(n,1);
      print(" of the preceding lines failed to match");
@.Hmm... n of the preceding...@>
      error;
    end if;
    return;
  end if;
end if@;
 
@ The |reset_input| procedure, which gets \.{AWEAVE} ready to read the
user's \.{AWEB} input, is used at the beginning of phases one and two.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |lex...@>=
  procedure reset_input;

@ @<Procedures in |lex...@>=
procedure @!reset_input is
begin TEXT_IO.RESET(aweb_file);
if TEXT_IO.IS_OPEN(change_file) then
  TEXT_IO.RESET(change_file);
end if;
line:=0; other_line:=0;@/
changing:=TRUE; prime_the_change_buffer; change_changing;@/
limit:=0; loc:=1; buffer(0):=@' '; input_has_ended:=FALSE;
end reset_input;
 
@ The |get_line| procedure is called when |loc>limit|; it puts the next
line of merged input into the buffer and updates the other variables
appropriately. A space is placed at the right end of the line.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |lex...@>=
  procedure get_line;

@ @<Procedures in |lex...@>=
procedure @!get_line is {inputs the next line}
begin <<restart>> if changing then
  changed_module(module_count):=TRUE;
else
  @<Read from |aweb_file| and maybe turn on |changing|@>;
end if;
if changing then
  @<Read from |change_file| and maybe turn off |changing|@>;
  if not changing then
    changed_module(module_count):=TRUE;
    goto restart;
  end if;
end if;
loc:=0; buffer(limit):=@' ';
end get_line;
 
@ @<Read from |aweb_file|...@>=
incr(line);
if not input_ln(aweb_file) then input_has_ended:=TRUE;
elsif (limit=change_limit) and
      ((buffer(0)=change_buffer(0)) and
      (change_limit>0)) then check_change;
end if@;
 
@ @<Read from |change_file|...@>=
incr(line);
if not input_ln(change_file) then
  err_print("! Change file ended without @@z");@/
@.\AT!z@> 
@.Change file ended...@>
  buffer(0..1):=(@'@@',@'z'); limit:=2;
end if;
if (limit>1) and then (buffer(0)=@'@@') then {check if the change has ended}
  if buffer(1) in @'X'..@'Z' then
    buffer(1):=buffer(1)+8#40#; {lowercasify}
  end if;
  if buffer(1) in @'x'..@'y' then
    loc:=2; err_print("! Where is the matching @@z?");
@.Where is the match...@>
  elsif buffer(1)=@'z' then
    prime_the_change_buffer; change_changing;
  end if;
end if@;

 
@ At the end of the program, we will tell the user if the change file
had a line that didn't match any relevant line in |aweb_file|.
 
@<Check that all changes have been read@>=
if change_limit/=0 then {|changing| is |FALSE|}
  buffer(0..change_limit):=change_buffer(0..change_limit);
  limit:=change_limit; changing:=TRUE; line:=other_line; loc:=change_limit;
  err_print("! Change file entry did not match");
@.Change file entry did not match@>
end if@;
 
@ Control codes in \.{AWEB}, which begin with `\.{@@}', are converted
into a numeric code designed to simplify \.{AWEAVE}'s logic; for example,
larger numbers are given to the control codes that denote more significant
milestones, and the code of |new_module| should be the largest of
all. Some of these numeric control codes take the place of ASCII
control codes that will not otherwise appear in the output of the
scanning routines.
@^ASCII code@>
 
@<Types...@>=
@!ignore: constant eight_bits:=0; {control code of no interest to \.{AWEAVE}}
@!verbatim: constant eight_bits:=8#2#; {extended ASCII alpha will not appear}
@!force_line: constant eight_bits:=8#3#; {extended ASCII beta will not appear}
@!begin_comment: constant eight_bits:=8#11#; {ASCII tab mark will not appear}
@!end_comment: constant eight_bits:=8#12#; {ASCII line feed will not appear}
@!character_tok: constant eight_bits:=8#14#; {ASCII form feed will not appear}
@!ascii_tok: constant eight_bits:=8#15#; {ASCII carriage return will not appear}
@!output_tok: constant eight_bits:=8#16#; {ASCII \.{DLE} will not appear}
@!double_dot: constant eight_bits:=8#40#; {ASCII space will not appear except in strings}
@!no_underline: constant eight_bits:=8#175#; {this code will be intercepted without confusion}
@!underline: constant eight_bits:=8#176#; {this code will be intercepted without confusion}
@!param: constant eight_bits:=8#177#; {ASCII delete will not appear}
@!xref_roman: constant eight_bits:=8#204#; {control code for `\.{@@\^}'}
@.\AT!\^@>
@!xref_wildcard: constant eight_bits:=8#205#; {control code for `\.{@@:}'}
@.\AT!:@>
@!xref_italic: constant eight_bits:=8#206#; {control code for `\.{@@i}'}
@.\AT!i@> 
@!xref_bold_face: constant eight_bits:=8#207#; {control code for `\.{@@b}'}
@.\AT!b@> 
@!xref_slanted: constant eight_bits:=8#210#; {control code for `\.{@@s}'}
@.\AT!s@> 
@!xref_typewriter: constant eight_bits:=8#211#; {control code for `\.{@@.}'}
@.\AT!.@>
@!xref_predefined: constant eight_bits:=8#212#; {control code for `\.{@@p}'}
@.\AT!p@> 
@!xref_reserved: constant eight_bits:=8#213#; {control code for `\.{@@r}'}
@.\AT!r@> 
@!TeX_string: constant eight_bits:=8#214#; {control code for `\.{@@t}'}
@.\AT!t@> 
@!join: constant eight_bits:=8#215#; {control code for `\.{@@\&}'}
@.\AT!\&@>
@!thin_space: constant eight_bits:=8#216#; {control code for `\.{@@,}'}
@.\AT!,@>
@!math_break: constant eight_bits:=8#217#; {control code for `\.{@@\char'174}'}
@.\AT!|@>
@!line_break: constant eight_bits:=8#220#; {control code for `\.{@@/}'}
@.\AT!/@>
@!big_line_break: constant eight_bits:=8#221#; {control code for `\.{@@\#}'}
@.\AT!\#@>
@!no_line_break: constant eight_bits:=8#222#; {control code for `\.{@@+}'}
@.\AT!+@>
@!pseudo_semi: constant eight_bits:=8#223#; {control code for `\.{@@;}'}
@.\AT!;@>
@!format: constant eight_bits:=8#224#; {control code for `\.{@@f}'}
@.\AT!f@> 
@!definition: constant eight_bits:=8#225#; {control code for `\.{@@d}'}
@.\AT!d@> 
@!begin_ada: constant eight_bits:=8#226#; {control code for `\.{@@a}'}
@.\AT!a@> 
@!module_name: constant eight_bits:=8#227#; {control code for `\.{@@<}'}
@.\AT!<@>
@!new_module: constant eight_bits:=8#230#; {control code for `\.{@@\ }' and `\.{@@*}'}
@.\AT!\ @> @.\AT!*@>

@ Control codes are converted from ASCII to \.{AWEAVE}'s internal
representation by the |control_code| routine.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |lex...@>=
 function control_code(c:ASCII_code)return eight_bits;

@ @<Procedures in |lex...@>=
function @!control_code(@!c:ASCII_code)return eight_bits is {convert |c|
  after \.{@@}}
begin case c is
when @'@@' => @+return @'@@'; {`quoted' at sign}
@.\AT!\AT!@>
when @''' => @+return ascii_tok; {precedes an ASCII constant}
@.\AT!'@>
when @'~' => @+return output_tok; {output file name}
@.\AT!\~@>
when @' ' ! tab_mark ! @'*' => @+return new_module; {beginning of a new module}
@.\AT!\ @> @.\AT!*@>
when @'=' => @+return verbatim; {verbatim string}
@.\AT!=@>
when @'\' => @+return force_line; {force line in \ADA\ output of \.{ATANGLE}}
@.\AT!\\@>
when @'D' ! @'d' => @+return definition; {macro definition}
@.\AT!d@> 
when @'F' ! @'f' => @+return format; {format definition}
@.\AT!f@> 
when @'{' => @+return begin_comment; {begin-comment delimiter}
@.\AT!\{@>
when @'}' => @+return end_comment; {end-comment delimiter}
@.\AT!\}@>
when @'A' ! @'a' => @+return begin_ada; {\ADA\ text in unnamed module}
@.\AT!a@> 
when @'&' => @+return join; {concatenate two tokens}
@.\AT!\&@>
when @'<' => @+return module_name; {beginning of a module name}
@.\AT!<@>
when @'>' => err_print("! Extra @@>");@/ 
  return ignore; {end of module name should not be discovered in this way}
@.\AT!>@>
@.Extra \AT!>@>
when @'T' ! @'t' => @+return TeX_string; {\TeX\ box within \ADA}
@.\AT!t@> 
when @'!' => @+return underline; {increment definition flag}
@.\AT!!@>
when @'?' => @+return no_underline; {decrement definition flag}
@.\AT!?@>
when @'^' => @+return xref_roman; {index entry to be typeset normally}
@.\AT!\^@>
when @':' => @+return xref_wildcard; {index entry to be in user format}
@.\AT!:@>
when @'i' ! @'I' => @+return xref_italic; {index entry to be in italic type}
@.\AT!i@> 
when @'b' ! @'B' => @+return xref_bold_face; {index entry to be in boldface type}
@.\AT!b@> 
when @'s' ! @'S' => @+return xref_slanted; {index entry to be in slanted type}
@.\AT!s@> 
when @'p' ! @'P' => @+return xref_predefined; {index entry like predefined identifier}
@.\AT!p@> 
when @'r' ! @'R' => @+return xref_reserved; {reserved word to be indexed}
@.\AT!r@> 
when @'.' => @+return xref_typewriter; {index entry to be in typewriter type}
@.\AT!.@>
when @',' => @+return thin_space; {puts extra space in \ADA\ format}
@.\AT!,@>
when @'|' => @+return math_break; {allows a break in a formula}
@.\AT!|@>
when @'/' => @+return line_break; {forces end-of-line in \ADA\ format}
@.\AT!/@>
when @'#' => @+return big_line_break; {forces end-of-line and some space besides}
@.\AT!\#@>
when @'+' => @+return no_line_break; {cancels end-of-line down to single space}
@.\AT!+@>
when @';' => @+return pseudo_semi; {acts like a semicolon, but is invisible}
@.\AT!;@>
when others => err_print("! Unknown control code");@/ return ignore;
@.Unknown control code@>
end case;
end control_code;
 
@ The |skip_limbo| routine is used on the first pass to skip through
portions of the input that are not in any modules, i.e., that precede
the first module. After this procedure has been called, the value of
|input_has_ended| will tell whether or not a new module has
actually been found.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |lex...@>=
  procedure skip_limbo;

@ @<Procedures in |lex...@>=
procedure @!skip_limbo is {skip to next module}
@!c:ASCII_code; {character following \.{@@}}
begin loop if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then return;
    end if;
  else  buffer(limit+1):=@'@@';
    while buffer(loc)/=@'@@' loop incr(loc); end loop;
    if loc<=limit then
      loc:=loc+2; c:=buffer(loc-1);
      if (c=@' ')or(c=tab_mark)or(c=@'*') then return; end if;
    end if;
  end if;
  end loop;
end skip_limbo;
 
@ The |skip_TeX| routine is used on the first pass to skip through
the \TeX\ code at the beginning of a module. It returns the next
control code or `\v' found in the input. A |new_module| is
assumed to exist at the very end of the file.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |lex...@>=
  function skip_TeX return eight_bits;

@ @<Procedures in |lex...@>=
function @!skip_TeX return eight_bits is {skip past pure \TeX\ code}
@!c:eight_bits; {control code found}
begin loop if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      return new_module; 
      end if;
    end if;
  buffer(limit+1):=@'@@';
  loop c:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
    if c=@'|' then return @'|'; end if;
    exit when c=@'@@';
  end loop;
  if loc<=limit then
    c:=control_code(buffer(loc)); incr(loc); return c;
    end if;
  end loop;
end skip_TeX;
 
@ The |skip_comment| routine is used on the first pass to skip
through \TeX\ code in \ADA\ comments. The |bal| parameter
tells how many left braces are assumed to have been scanned when
this routine is called, and the procedure returns a corresponding
value of |bal| at the point that scanning has stopped. Scanning
stops either at a `\v' that introduces \ADA\ text,
in which case the returned value is positive, or it stops at the
end of the comment, in which case the returned value is zero.
The scanning also stops in anomalous situations when the comment
doesn't end or when it contains an illegal use of \.{@@}.
One should call |skip_comment(1)| when beginning to scan a comment.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |lex...@>=
  function skip_comment(bal:eight_bits)return eight_bits;

@ @<Procedures in |lex...@>=
function @!skip_comment(@!bal:eight_bits)return eight_bits is {skips \TeX\
  code in comments}
@!b:eight_bits:=bal; {depth of brace nesting}
@!c:ASCII_code; {the current character}
begin loop if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      return 0; {an error message will occur in phase two}
      end if;
    end if;
  c:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
  if c=@'|' then return b; end if;
  @<Do special things when |c=@'@@', @'\', @'{', @'}'|; |return@;| at end@>;
  end loop;
end skip_comment;
 
@ @<Do special things when |c=@'@@'...@>=
if c=@'@@' then
  c:=buffer(loc);
  if (c/=@' ')and(c/=tab_mark)and(c/=@'*') then incr(loc);
  else  decr(loc); return 0; {an error message will occur in phase two}
  end if;
elsif (c=@'\')and(buffer(loc)/=@'@@') then incr(loc);
elsif c=@'{' then incr(b);
elsif c=@'}' then
  decr(b);
  if b=0 then return 0; end if;
end if@;
 
@* Inputting the next token.
As stated above, \.{AWEAVE}'s most interesting lexical scanning routine is the
|get_next| function that inputs the next token of \ADA\ input. However,
|get_next| is not especially complicated.

The result of |get_next| is either an ASCII code for some special character,
or it is a special code representing a pair of characters (e.g., `\.{:=}'
or `\.{..}'), or it is the numeric value computed by the |control_code|
procedure, or it is one of the following special codes:
 
\yskip\hang |exponent|: The `\.E' in a real constant.
 
\yskip\hang |identifier|: In this case the global variables |id_first|
and |id_loc| will have been set to the appropriate values needed by the
|id_lookup| routine.
 
\yskip\hang |str|: In this case the global variables |id_first| and
|id_loc| will have been set to the beginning and ending-plus-one locations
in the buffer.  The string ends with the first reappearance of its initial
delimiter; thus, for example, $$\.{"This is ""not"" a single string"}$$
will be treated as three consecutive strings, the first being \.{"This
is"}.
 
\yskip\noindent There are some special cases that need to be considered:

\yskip\hang |character_tok| is returned if a character literal, e.g.\
 \.{\'a\'}, is sensed and |id_first| and |id_loc| are set appropriate
 as described for |str|.

\yskip\hang based literals: Between two \# signs characters are treated
  as digits; this is done be means of the global variable
  |scanning_based_number|.

\yskip\noindent Furthermore, some of the control codes cause
|get_next| to take additional actions:
 
\yskip\hang $|xref_roman|,\ldots,|TeX_string|$: The values of
|id_first| and |id_loc| will be set so that the string in question appears
in |buffer(id_first..(id_loc-1))|.
 
\yskip\hang |module_name|: In this case the global variable |cur_module| will
point to the |byte_start| entry for the module name that has just been scanned.
 
\yskip\hang |output_tok|: The file name is treated the same way
as decribed above for |str|.

\yskip\hang |ascii_tok|: The ASCII code constant is treated the same way
as described above for |character_tok|.

\yskip\noindent If |get_next| sees `\.{@@!}' or `\.{@@?}',
it increments respectively decrements |xref_switch| by |def_flag|, 
supposed that |0<=xref_switch<=body_flag| afterwards,  
and goes on to the next token.
@.\AT!!@> @.\AT!?@>
 
@<Types...@>= 
@!exponent: constant eight_bits:=8#201#; {\.E or \.e following a digit}
@!str: constant eight_bits:=8#202#; {\ADA\ string}
@!identifier: constant eight_bits:=8#203#; {\ADA\ identifier or reserved word}
@#
@!cur_module: name_pointer; {name of module just scanned}
@!scanning_based_number: BOOLEAN:=FALSE; {are we scanning a based number?} 

@ As one might expect, |get_next| consists mostly of a big switch
that branches to the various special cases that can arise. Some care is
needed for the handling of \ADA's based literals.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |lex...@>=
  function get_next return eight_bits;

@ @<Procedures in |lex...@>=
function @!get_next return eight_bits is {produces the next input token}
@!c:eight_bits; {the current character}
@!d:eight_bits; {the next character}
@!j,@!k:long_name_index; {indices into |mod_text|}
begin <<restart>> if loc>limit then
  get_line;
  if input_has_ended then
    return new_module;
  elsif scanning_based_number then
    err_print("! Improper based number, # sign missing");
    {a based literal should fit in one line}
@.Improper based number...@>
    end if;
  end if;
c:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
if scanning_based_number then
  if c=@'#' then scanning_based_number:=FALSE; end if;
  return c;
end if;
case c is
when @'#' => if (loc>1) and then (buffer(loc-2) in @'0'..@'9') then
               scanning_based_number:=TRUE;
             end if; return @'#';
when @'A'..@'Z' ! @'a'..@'z' => @<Get an identifier@>;
when @''' => @<Get a character token@>;
when @'"' => @<Get a string@>;
when @'@@' => @<Get control code and possible module name@>;
@/@t\4@>@<Compress two-symbol combinations like `\.{:=}'@>@;
when @' ' ! tab_mark => goto restart; {ignore spaces and tabs}
when others => null;
end case;
return c;
end get_next;
 

@ 
@d compress(#)==if loc<=limit then c:=#; incr(loc); end if@;
 
@<Compress two-symbol...@>=
when @'.' => if buffer(loc)=@'.' then compress(double_dot);
             end if;
@...@>
when @':' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(left_arrow);
             end if;
@.:=@>
when @'=' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(equivalence_sign);
             elsif buffer(loc)=@'>' then compress(right_arrow);
             end if;
@.==@> @.=>@>
when @'>' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(greater_or_equal);
             elsif buffer(loc)=@'>' then compress(right_label_bracket);
             end if;
@.>=@> @.>>@>
when @'<' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(less_or_equal);
             elsif buffer(loc)=@'<' then compress(left_label_bracket);
             elsif buffer(loc)=@'>' then compress(box_sign);
             end if;
@.<=@> @.<<@> @.<>@>
when @'/' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(not_equal);
             end if;
@./=@>
when @'*' => if buffer(loc)=@'*' then compress(double_star);
             end if;
@.**@>

@ @<Get an identifier@>=
if (((c=@'E')or(c=@'e'))and(loc>1)) and then
  ((buffer(loc-2) in @'0'..@'9') or buffer(loc-2)=@'#') then c:=exponent;
end if;
if c/=exponent then
  decr(loc); id_first:=loc;
  loop incr(loc); d:=buffer(loc);@/
  exit when (d not in @'0'..@'9') and (d not in @'A'..@'Z') and
            (d not in @'a'..@'z') and (d/=@'_');
  end loop;
  c:=identifier;
  id_loc:=loc;
end if@;
 
@ A string that starts and ends with double quote marks is
scanned by the following piece of the program.
 
@<Get a string@>=
id_first:=loc-1;
loop d:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
if loc>limit then
  err_print("! String constant didn't end"); @/
@.String constant didn't end@>
  loc:=limit; d:=c;
  end if;
  exit when d=c;
end loop;
id_loc:=loc; c:=str@;
 
@ After an \.{@@} sign has been scanned, the next character tells us
whether there is more work to do.
 
@<Get control code and possible module name@>=
c:=control_code(buffer(loc)); incr(loc);
case c is
when underline =>
  if xref_switch<body_flag then xref_switch:=xref_switch+def_flag; end if;
  goto restart;
when no_underline =>
  if xref_switch>0 then xref_switch:=xref_switch-def_flag; end if;
  goto restart;
when xref_roman..TeX_string =>
  @<Scan to the next \.{@@>}@>;
when module_name =>
  @<Scan the module name and make |cur_module| point to it@>;
when verbatim ! output_tok =>
  @<Scan a verbatim or output string@>;
when ascii_tok =>
  @<Scan an ASCII token@>;
when others => null;
end case@;
 
@ The occurrence of a module name sets |xref_switch| to zero,
because the module name might (for example) follow \&{type}.
 
@<Scan the module name...@>=
@<Put module name into |mod_text(1..k)|@>;
if (k>3) and then (mod_text(k-2..k)=(@'.',@'.',@'.')) then
    cur_module:=prefix_lookup(k-3);
else cur_module:=mod_lookup(k);
end if;
xref_switch:=0@;
 
@ Module names are placed into the |mod_text| array with consecutive spaces,
tabs, and carriage-returns replaced by single spaces. There will be no
spaces at the beginning or the end. (We set |mod_text(0):=@' '| to facilitate
this, since the |mod_lookup| routine uses |mod_text(1)| as the first
character of the name.)
 
@<Set init...@>=mod_text(0):=@' ';
 
@ @<Put module name...@>=
k:=0;
loop if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      err_print("! Input ended in section name");@/
@.Input ended in section name@>
      loc:=1;@/
      exit;
      end if;
    end if;
  d:=buffer(loc);
  @<If end of name, |exit@;|@>;
  incr(loc); if k<longest_name-1 then incr(k); end if;
  if (d=@' ')or(d=tab_mark) then
    d:=@' '; if mod_text(k-1)=@' ' then decr(k); end if;
    end if;
  mod_text(k):=d;
  end loop;
@<Check for overlong name@>;
if (mod_text(k)=@' ')and(k>0) then decr(k);
end if@;
 
@ @<If end of name,...@>=
if d=@'@@' then
  d:=buffer(loc+1);
  if d=@'>' then
    loc:=loc+2; @/
    exit;
    end if;
  if (d=@' ')or(d=tab_mark)or(d=@'*') then
    err_print("! Section name didn't end");@/ exit;
@.Section name didn't end@>
    end if;
  incr(k); mod_text(k):=@'@@'; incr(loc); {now |d=buffer(loc)| again}
  end if@;
 
@ @<Check for overlong name@>=
if k>=longest_name-2 then
  print_nl("! Section name too long: ");
@.Section name too long@>
  for i in 1..25 loop print(xchr(mod_text(i))); end loop;
  print("..."); mark_harmless;
  end if@;
 
@ @<Scan to the next...@>=
id_first:=loc; buffer(limit+1):=@'@@';
while buffer(loc)/=@'@@' loop incr(loc); end loop;
id_loc:=loc;
if loc>limit then
  err_print("! Control text didn't end");@/ loc:=limit;
@.Control text didn't end@>
else  loc:=loc+2;
  if buffer(loc-1)/=@'>' then
    err_print("! Control codes are forbidden in control text");
@.Control codes are forbidden...@>
  end if;
end if@;
 
@ A verbatim \ADA\ string respectively an output string will be treated like 
ordinary strings, but with no surrounding delimiters.  At the present point 
in the program we have |buffer(loc-1)=verbatim| or 
|buffer(loc-1)=output_tok|; we must set |id_first| to the beginning
of the string itself, and |id_loc| to its ending-plus-one location in the
buffer.  We also set |loc| to the position just after the ending delimiter.
 
@<Scan a verbatim or output string@>=
id_first:=loc; incr(loc);
buffer(limit+1):=@'@@'; buffer(limit+2):=@'>';
while (buffer(loc)/=@'@@')or(buffer(loc+1)/=@'>') loop incr(loc); end loop;
if loc>=limit then err_print("! Verbatim string didn't end");
@.Verbatim string didn't end@>
end if;
id_loc:=loc; loc:=loc+2@;


@ Getting a character token and getting an ASCII token is essentially
the same: |id_first| is set to the position of the first `\.\'' and
|id_loc| to the position after the final `\.\''.

@<Get a character token@>=
id_first:=loc-1;
if buffer(loc+1)=@''' then
  loc:=loc+2; id_loc:=loc;
  c:=character_tok;
elsif buffer(loc..loc+2)=(@'@@',@'@@',@''') then
  loc:=loc+3; id_loc:=loc;
  c:=character_tok;
end if@;
 
@ @<Scan an ASCII...@>=
id_first:=loc-1; incr(loc);
if buffer(loc)/=@''' then
  if buffer(loc-1..loc)/=(@'@@',@'@@') then
    err_print("! Improper ASCII-code sequence, ' sign missing");
@.Improper ASCII-code sequence...@>
  else incr(loc);
  end if;
end if;
incr(loc); id_loc:=loc@;

@* Phase one processing.
We now have accumulated enough subroutines to make it possible to carry out
\.{AWEAVE}'s first pass over the source file. If everything works right,
both phase one and phase two of \.{AWEAVE} will assign the same numbers to
modules, and these numbers will agree with what \.{ATANGLE} does.
 
The global variable |next_control| often contains the most recent output of
|get_next|; in interesting cases, this will be the control code that
ended a module or part of a module.
 
@<Types...@>=@!next_control:eight_bits; {control code waiting to be acting upon}
 
@ The overall processing strategy in phase one has the following
straightforward outline.
 
@<Phase I: Read all the user's text and store the cross references@>=
phase_one:=TRUE; phase_three:=FALSE;
reset_input;
module_count:=0; skip_limbo; change_exists:=FALSE;
while not input_has_ended loop
  @<Store cross reference data for the current module@>;
end loop;
changed_module(module_count):=change_exists;
  {the index changes if anything does}
phase_one:=FALSE; {prepare for second phase}
@<Print error messages about unused or undefined module names@>@;
 
@ @<Store cross reference data...@>=
incr(module_count);
if module_count=max_modules then overflow("section number"); end if;
changed_module(module_count):=FALSE; {it will become |TRUE| if any line changes}
if buffer(loc-1)=@'*' then
  print("*"); print_int(module_count,1);
  update_terminal; {print a progress report}
  end if;
@<Store cross references in the \TeX\ part of a module@>;
@<Store cross references in the \(definition part of a module@>;
@<Store cross references in the \(\ADA\ part of a module@>;
if changed_module(module_count) then change_exists:=TRUE; end if@;
 
@ The |ADA_xref| subroutine stores references to identifiers in
\ADA\ text material beginning with the current value of |next_control|
and continuing until |next_control| is `\.\{' or `\v', or until the next
``milestone'' is passed (i.e., |next_control>=format|). If
|next_control>=format| when |ADA_xref| is called, nothing will happen;
but if |next_control=@'|'| upon entry, the procedure assumes that this is
the `\v' preceding \ADA\ text that is to be processed.
 
The program uses the fact that our internal code numbers satisfy
the relations |xref_roman=identifier+roman|, |xref_wildcard=identifier
+wildcard|, $\ldots$, |xref_typewriter=identifier+typewriter|,
and |normal=0|.

After \&{entry}, \&{for}, \&{function}, \&{package}, \&{procedure}, 
\&{subtype}, \&{task}, and \&{type} |xref_switch| is set to |def_flag|; 
after \&{accept} and \&{body} it is set to |body_flag|.
@rentry@> @rfor@> @rfunction@> @rpackage@> @rprocedure@> @rsubtype@>
@rtask@> @rtype@> @raccept@> @rbody@>

@<Specification of procedures visible from |first...@>=
procedure ADA_xref;

@ @<Procedures in |first...@>=
procedure @!ADA_xref is {makes cross references for \ADA\ identifiers}
@!p:name_pointer; {a referenced name}
@!i:INTEGER; {temporary ilk code of |p|}
begin while next_control<format loop
  if next_control in identifier..xref_predefined then
    p:=id_lookup(next_control-identifier);
    if (ilk(p)=body_like)or(ilk(p)=type_like) then
      xref_switch:=0; {no index entry for \&{body} and \&{type}}
    end if;
    new_xref(p);
    if (ilk(p)=proc_like)or(ilk(p)=type_like) then
      xref_switch:=def_flag; {implied |def_flag|}
    elsif (ilk(p)=accept_like)or(ilk(p)=body_like) then
      xref_switch:=body_flag; {implied |body_flag|}
    end if;
  elsif next_control=xref_reserved then
    p:=id_lookup(normal); i:=ilk(p); ilk(p):=normal; new_xref(p);
    ilk(p):=i;
  end if;
  next_control:=get_next;
  if (next_control=@'|')or(next_control=@'{') then return; end if;
  end loop;
end ADA_xref;
 
@ The |outer_xref| subroutine is like |ADA_xref| but it begins
with |next_control/=@'|'| and ends with |next_control>=format|. Thus, it
handles \ADA\ text with embedded comments.

@<Procedures in |first...@>= 
procedure @!outer_xref is {extension of |ADA_xref|}
@!bal:eight_bits; {brace level in comment}
begin while next_control<format loop
  if next_control/=@'{' then ADA_xref;
  else  bal:=skip_comment(1); next_control:=@'|';
    while bal>0 loop
      ADA_xref;
      if next_control=@'|' then bal:=skip_comment(bal);
      else bal:=0; {an error will be reported in phase two}
      end if;
    end loop;
  end if;
end loop;
end outer_xref;

@ During the definition and \ADA\ parts of a module, cross references
are made for all identifiers except reserved words; however, the
identifiers in a format definition are referenced even if they are
reserved. The \TeX\ code in comments is, of course, ignored, except for
\ADA\ portions enclosed in \ab; the text of a module name is skipped
entirely, even if it contains \ab\ constructions.
 
The variables |lhs| and |rhs| point to the respective identifiers involved
in a format definition.

Additionally to the points just stated a reserved identifier is
referenced by means of the `\.{@@r}' control code; the variable
|temp_ilk| contains the |ilk| of an identifier during the |new_xref|
subroutine is executing, because we have to set the |ilk| to
|normal| before the call.

@<Types...@>=
@!lhs,@!rhs:name_pointer; {indices into |byte_start| for format identifiers}
@!temp_ilk:sixteen_bits; {temporarily contains the |ilk| of |lhs|}

 
@ In the \TeX\ part of a module, cross reference entries are made only for
the identifiers in \ADA\ texts enclosed in \ab, or for control texts
enclosed in \.{@@\^}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>} or \.{@@.}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>}
or \.{@@:}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>}
or \.{@@i}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>}
or \.{@@p}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>}
or \.{@@r}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>}
or \.{@@b}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>}
or \.{@@s}$\,\ldots\,$\.{@@>}.

@.\AT!\^@> @.\AT!.@> @.\AT!:@> @.\AT!i@> @.\AT!p@> @.\AT!r@> @.\AT!b@>
@.\AT!a@>
 
@<Store cross references in the \T...@>=
loop next_control:=skip_TeX;
case next_control is
when underline => 
  if xref_switch<body_flag then
    xref_switch:=xref_switch+def_flag;
  end if;
when no_underline => 
  if xref_switch>0 then
    xref_switch:=xref_switch-def_flag;
  end if;
when @'|' => ADA_xref;
when xref_roman..xref_predefined ! module_name =>
  loc:=loc-2; next_control:=get_next; {scan to \.{@@>}}
  if next_control/=module_name then
    new_xref(id_lookup(next_control-identifier));
  end if;
when xref_reserved =>
  loc:=loc-2; next_control:=get_next; {scan to \.{@@>}}
  lhs:=id_lookup(normal); temp_ilk:=ilk(lhs); {get the |ilk|}
  ilk(lhs):=normal; new_xref(lhs); {make the cross reference}
  ilk(lhs):=temp_ilk; {reset the |ilk|}
when others => null;
end case;
exit when next_control>=format;
end loop@;
 
@ When we get to the following code we have |next_control>=format|.
 
@<Store cross references in the \(d...@>=
while next_control<=definition loop {|format| or |definition|}
  xref_switch:=def_flag; {implied \.{@@!}}
@.\AT!!@>
  if next_control=definition then next_control:=get_next;
  else @<Process a format definition@>;
  end if;
  outer_xref;
end loop@;
 
@ Error messages for improper format definitions will be issued in phase
two. Our job in phase one is to define the |ilk| of a properly formatted
identifier, and to fool the |new_xref| routine into thinking that the
identifier on the right-hand side of the format definition is not a
reserved word.
 
@<Process a form...@>=
next_control:=get_next;
if next_control=identifier then
  lhs:=id_lookup(normal); ilk(lhs):=normal; new_xref(lhs);
  next_control:=get_next;
  if next_control=equivalence_sign then
    next_control:=get_next;
    if next_control=identifier then
      rhs:=id_lookup(normal);
      ilk(lhs):=ilk(rhs); ilk(rhs):=normal; new_xref(rhs);
      ilk(rhs):=ilk(lhs); next_control:=get_next;
      end if;
    end if;
  end if@;
 
@ Finally, when the \TeX\ and definition parts have been treated, we have
|next_control>=begin_ada|.
 
@<Store cross references in the \(\A...@>=
if next_control<=module_name then {|begin_ada| or |module_name|}
  if next_control=begin_ada then mod_xref_switch:=0;
  else mod_xref_switch:=def_flag;
  end if;
  loop if next_control=module_name then new_mod_xref(cur_module); end if;
    next_control:=get_next; @/
    outer_xref; @/
    exit when next_control>module_name;
  end loop;
end if@;
 
@ After phase one has looked at everything, we want to check that each
module name was both defined and used.
The variable |cur_xref| will point to cross references for the
current module name of interest.
 
@<Types...@>=@!cur_xref:xref_number; {temporary cross reference pointer}
 
@ The following recursive procedure
walks through the tree of module names and prints out anomalies.
@^recursion@>
 
@<Procedures in |first...@>=
procedure @!mod_check(@!p:name_pointer) is {print anomalies in subtree |p|}
begin if p>0 then
  mod_check(llink(p));@/
  cur_xref:=xref(p);
  if num(cur_xref)<def_flag then
    print_nl("! Never defined: <"); print_id(p);
@.Never defined: <section name>@>
    print(">"); mark_harmless;
    end if;
  while num(cur_xref)>=def_flag loop cur_xref:=xlink(cur_xref); end loop;
  if cur_xref=0 then
    print_nl("! Never used: <"); print_id(p); print(">");
@.Never used: <section name>@>
    mark_harmless;
    end if;
  mod_check(rlink(p));
  end if;
end mod_check;
 
@ @<Print error messages about un...@>=@+mod_check(root)@;
 
@* Low-level output routines.
The \TeX\ output is supposed to appear in lines at most |line_length|
characters long, so we place it into an output buffer. During the output
process, |out_line| will hold the current line number of the line about to
be output.
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype length_index is INTEGER range 0..line_length;
@!out_buf:array(length_index) of ASCII_code; {assembled characters}
@!out_ptr:length_index; {number of characters in |out_buf|}
@!out_line: INTEGER; {coordinates of next line to be output}
 
@ The |flush_buffer| routine empties the buffer up to a given breakpoint,
and moves any remaining characters to the beginning of the next line.
If the |per_cent| parameter is |TRUE|, a |@'%'| is appended to the line
that is being output; in this case the breakpoint |b| should be strictly
less than |line_length|. If the |per_cent| parameter is |FALSE|,
trailing blanks are suppressed.
The characters emptied from the buffer form a new line of output.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |output|@>=
  procedure flush_buffer(b:eight_bits; per_cent:BOOLEAN);

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
procedure @!flush_buffer(@!b:eight_bits;@!per_cent:BOOLEAN) is
  {outputs |out_buf(1..b)|, where |b<=out_ptr|}
@!j:length_index:=b;
begin 
if not per_cent then {remove trailing blanks}
  loop exit when (j=0) or else (out_buf(j)/=@' ');@/
    decr(j);
    end loop;
end if;
for k in 1..j loop TEXT_IO.PUT(TeX_file,xchr(out_buf(k))); end loop;
if per_cent then TEXT_IO.PUT(TeX_file,xchr(@'%'));
end if;
TEXT_IO.NEW_LINE(TeX_file); incr(out_line);
if b<out_ptr then 
   out_buf(1..out_ptr-b):=out_buf(b+1..out_ptr);
end if;
out_ptr:=out_ptr-b;
end flush_buffer;
 
@ When we are copying \TeX\ source material, we retain line breaks
that occur in the input, except that an empty line is not
output when the \TeX\ source line was nonempty. For example, a line
of the \TeX\ file that contains only an index cross-reference entry
will not be copied. The |finish_line| routine is called just before
|get_line| inputs a new line, and just after a line break token has
been emitted during the output of translated \ADA\ text.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |output|@>=
  procedure finish_line;

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
procedure @!finish_line is {do this at the end of a line}
begin if out_ptr>0 then flush_buffer(out_ptr,FALSE);
else  for k in 0..limit loop
    if (buffer(k)/=@' ')and(buffer(k)/=tab_mark) then return; end if;
    end loop;
  flush_buffer(0,FALSE);
  end if;
end finish_line;
 
@ In particular, the |finish_line| procedure is called near the very
beginning of phase two. We initialize the output variables in a slightly
tricky way so that the first line of the output file will be
`\.{\\input awebmac}'.
@.\\input awebmac@>
 
@<Set init...@>=
out_ptr:=1; out_line:=1; out_buf(1):=@'c'; 
TEXT_IO.PUT(TeX_file,"\input awebma");
 
@ When we wish to append the character |c| to the output buffer, we write
`$|out1|(c)$'; this will cause the buffer to be emptied if it was already
full. Similarly, `$|out2|(c_1)(c_2)$' appends a pair of characters.
A line break will occur at a space or after a single-nonletter
\TeX\ control sequence.
 
@d out1(#)==
  if out_ptr=line_length then break_out; end if;
  incr(out_ptr); out_buf(out_ptr):=#@;
@d out2(#)==out1(#); out1@;
@d out3(#)==out1(#); out2@;
@d out4(#)==out1(#); out3@;
@d out5(#)==out1(#); out4@;
 
@ The |break_out| routine is called just before the output buffer is about
to overflow. To make this routine a little faster, we initialize position
0 of the output buffer to `\.\\'; this character isn't really output.
 
@<Set init...@>=
out_buf(0):=@'\';
 
@ A long line is broken at a blank space or just before a backslash that isn't
preceded by another backslash. In the latter case, a |@'%'| is output at
the break.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |output|@>=
  procedure break_out;

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
procedure @!break_out is {finds a way to break the output line}
@!k:length_index:=out_ptr; {index into |out_buf|}
@!c,@!d:ASCII_code; {characters from the buffer}
begin 
loop if k=0 then
    @<Print warning message, break the line, |return@;|@>; end if;
  d:=out_buf(k);
  if d=@' ' then
    flush_buffer(k,FALSE); return;
  end if;
  if (d=@'\')and(out_buf(k-1)/=@'\') then {in this case |k>1|}
    flush_buffer(k-1,TRUE); return;
  end if;
  decr(k);
  end loop;
end break_out;
 
@ We get to this module only in unusual cases that the entire output line
consists of a string of backslashes followed by a string of nonblank
non-backslashes. In such cases it is almost always safe to break the
line by putting a |@'%'| just before the last character.
 
@<Print warning message...@>=
print_nl("! Line had to be broken (output l."); print_int(out_line,1);
@.Line had to be broken@>
print_ln("):");
for j in 1..out_ptr-1 loop print(xchr(out_buf(j))); end loop;
new_ln; mark_harmless;
flush_buffer(out_ptr-1,TRUE); return@;
 
@ Here is a procedure that outputs a module number in decimal notation.
 
@<Types...@>=@!dig:array(0..4) of INTEGER range 0..9; {digits to output}
 
@ The number to be converted by |out_mod| is known to be less than
|def_flag|, so it cannot have more than five decimal digits.  If
the module is changed, we output `\.{\\*}' just after the number and if
|c>1| we output `$\.(\,c\,\.)$'.


@<Specification of procedures visible from |output|@>=
  procedure out_mod(m:INTEGER;c:INTEGER:=1);

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
 procedure @!out_mod(@!m:INTEGER;@!c:INTEGER:=1) is {output a module number}
 @!k: INTEGER range 0..5; {index into |dig|}
 @!a:INTEGER; {accumulator}
 begin a:=m;
 @<Output the digits of |a|@>;
 if changed_module(m) then out2(@'\')(@'*'); end if;
 @.\\*@>
 if c>1 then
   out1(@'(');
 @.(...)@>
   a:=c;
   @<Output the digits...@>;
   out1(@')');
 end if;
 end out_mod;

@ Here we output the digits of |a| using the |dig| array.
@<Output the digits...@>=
 k:=0;
 loop dig(k):=a mod 10; a:=a/10; incr(k); @/
 exit when a=0;
 end loop;
 loop decr(k); out1(dig(k)+@'0'); @/
 exit when k=0;
 end loop@;

@ The |out_name| subroutine is used to output an identifier or index
entry, enclosing it in braces.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |out...@>=
  procedure out_name(p:name_pointer);

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
procedure @!out_name(@!p:name_pointer)is {outputs a name}
@!w:w_range; {row of |byte_mem|}
begin out1(@'{'); w:=p mod ww;
for k in byte_start(p)..byte_start(p+ww)-1 loop
  if byte_mem(w,k)=@'_' then out1(@'\'); end if;
@.\\_@>
  out1(byte_mem(w,k));
  end loop;
out1(@'}');
end out_name;
 
@* Routines that copy \TeX\ material.
During phase two, we use the subroutines |copy_limbo|, |copy_TeX|, and
|copy_comment| in place of the analogous |skip_limbo|, |skip_TeX|, and
|skip_comment| that were used in phase one.
 
The |copy_limbo| routine, for example, takes \TeX\ material that is not
part of any module and transcribes it almost verbatim to the output file.
No `\.{@@}' signs should occur in such material except in `\.{@@@@}'
@.\AT!\AT!@>
pairs; such pairs are replaced by singletons.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |output|@>=
  procedure copy_limbo;

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
procedure @!copy_limbo is {copy \TeX\ code until the next module begins}
@!c:ASCII_code; {character following \.{@@} sign}
begin loop if loc>limit then
    finish_line; get_line;
    if input_has_ended then return; end if;
  else  buffer(limit+1):=@'@@';@/
    @<Copy up to control code, |return@;| if finished@>;
  end if;
end loop;
end copy_limbo;
 
@ @<Copy up to control...@>=
while buffer(loc)/=@'@@' loop
  out1(buffer(loc)); incr(loc);
  end loop;
if loc<=limit then
  loc:=loc+2; c:=buffer(loc-1);
  if (c=@' ')or(c=tab_mark)or(c=@'*') then return; end if;
  if (c/=@'z')and(c/=@'Z') then
    out1(@'@@');
    if c/=@'@@' then err_print("! Double @@ required outside of sections");
@.Double \AT! required...@>
    end if;
  end if;
end if@;
 
@ The |copy_TeX| routine processes the \TeX\ code at the beginning of a
module; for example, the words you are now reading were copied in this
way. It returns the next control code or `\v' found in the input.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |out...@>=
  function copy_TeX return eight_bits;

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
function @!copy_TeX return eight_bits is {copy pure \TeX\ material}
@!c:eight_bits; {control code found}
begin loop if loc>limit then
    finish_line; get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      return new_module; 
      end if;
    end if;
  buffer(limit+1):=@'@@'; @/
  @<Copy up to `\v' or control code, |return c| if finished@>;
  end loop;
end copy_TeX;
 
@ We don't copy spaces or tab marks into the beginning of a line. This
makes the test for empty lines in |finish_line| work.
 
@<Copy up to `\v'...@>=
loop c:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
if c=@'|' then return @'|'; end if;
if c/=@'@@' then
  out1(c);
  if (out_ptr=1)and((c=@' ')or(c=tab_mark)) then decr(out_ptr); end if;
  end if;
exit when c=@'@@';
end loop;
if loc<=limit then
  c:=control_code(buffer(loc)); incr(loc);
  return c;
end if@;
 
@ The |copy_comment| uses and returns a brace-balance value, following the
conventions of |skip_comment| above. Instead of copying the \TeX\ material
into the output buffer, this procedure copies it into the token memory.
The abbreviation |app_tok(t)| is used to append token |t| to the current
token list, and it also makes sure that it is possible to append at least
one further token without overflow.
 
@d app_tok(#)==if tok_ptr+2>max_toks then overflow("token"); end if;
  tok_mem(tok_ptr):=#; incr(tok_ptr)@;

@<Specification of procedures visible from |output|@>=
  function copy_comment(bal:eight_bits)return eight_bits;

@ @<Procedures in |output|@>=
function @!copy_comment(@!bal:eight_bits) return eight_bits is  
         {copies \TeX\ code in comments}
@!c:ASCII_code; {current character being copied}
@!b:eight_bits:=bal; {brace-balance value}
begin loop if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      err_print("! Input ended in mid-comment");@/
@.Input ended in mid-comment@>
      loc:=1; @<Clear |b| and |return 0@;|@>;
      end if;
    end if;
  c:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
  if c=@'|' then return b; end if;
  app_tok(c); @/
  @<Copy special things when |c=@'@@', @'\', @'{', @'}'|;
    |return@;| at end@>;
  end loop;
end copy_comment;
 
@ @<Copy special things when |c=@'@@'...@>=
if c=@'@@' then
  incr(loc);
  if buffer(loc-1)/=@'@@' then
    err_print("! Illegal use of @@ in comment"); @/
@.Illegal use of \AT!...@>
    loc:=loc-2; decr(tok_ptr); @<Clear |b|...@>;
    end if;
elsif (c=@'\')and(buffer(loc)/=@'@@') then
  app_tok(buffer(loc)); incr(loc);
elsif c=@'{' then incr(b);
elsif c=@'}' then
  decr(b);
  if b=0 then return 0; end if;
end if@;
 
@ When the comment has terminated abruptly due to an error, we output
enough right braces to keep \TeX\ happy.
 
@<Clear |b|...@>=
app_tok(@' '); {this is done in case the previous character was `\.\\'}
while b>0 loop app_tok(@'}'); decr(b);
end loop;
return 0@;
 
@* Parsing.
The most intricate part of \.{AWEAVE} is its mechanism for converting
\ADA-like code into \TeX\ code, and we might as well plunge into this
aspect of the program now. A ``bottom up'' approach is used to parse the
\ADA-like material, since \.{AWEAVE} must deal with fragmentary
constructions whose overall ``part of speech'' is not known.
 
At the lowest level, the input is represented as a sequence of entities
that we shall call {\it scraps}, where each scrap of information consists
of two parts, its {\it category} and its {\it translation}. The category
is essentially a syntactic class, and the translation is a token list that
represents \TeX\ code. Rules of syntax and semantics tell us how to
combine adjacent scraps into larger ones, and if we are lucky an entire
\ADA\ text that starts out as hundreds of small scraps will join
together into one gigantic scrap whose translation is the desired \TeX\
code. If we are unlucky, we will be left with several scraps that don't
combine; their translations will simply be output, one by one.
 
The combination rules are given as context-sensitive productions that are
applied from left to right. Suppose that we are currently working on the
sequence of scraps $s_1\,s_2\ldots s_n$. We try first to find the longest
production that applies to an initial substring $s_1\,s_2\ldots\,$; but if
no such productions exist, we find to find the longest production
applicable to the next substring $s_2\,s_3\ldots\,$; and if that fails, we
try to match $s_3\,s_4\ldots\,$, etc.
 
A production applies if the category codes have a given pattern. For
example, one of the productions is
$$|open_scrap|\;|decl|\;\RA\;|open_scrap|$$
and it means that two consecutive scraps whose respective categories are
|open_scrap| and |decl| are con\-verted to one scrap whose category
is |open_scrap|. This production also has an associated rule that
tells how to combine the translation parts:
$$O_2=O_1\,|pdollar|\,D\,|pdollar|\,\.{\\,}\,\hbox{|opt|\thinspace\tt5}$$
This means that the new |open_scrap| scrap has a translation $O_2$ composed of 
the translation $O_1$ of the original
|open_scrap| scrap followed by |pdollar| followed by the translation |D| of the 
|decl| scrap followed by |pdollar| followed
by `\.{\\,}' followed by `|opt|' followed by `\.5'. (In the \TeX\ file,
this will specify an additional thin space after the |pdollar|, followed
by an optional line break with penalty 50.) Translation rules use subscripts
to distinguish between translations of scraps whose categories have the
same initial letter; these subscripts are assigned from left to right.
 
There is also the production rule
$$|loop_scrap|\;\RA\;|beginning|$$
(meaning that a \&{loop} begins a block-like \ADA\ statement). Since
productions are applied from left to right, this rule will be activated
only if the |loop_scrap| is not preceded by scraps that match other productions.
 
The translation rule corresponding to $|loop_scrap|\;\RA\;|beginning|$ is
$$B=L$$
but we shall not mention translation rules in the common case that the
translation of the new scrap on the right-hand side is simply the
concatenation of the disappearing scraps on the left-hand side.
 
@ Here is a list of the category codes that scraps can have.

@<Types...@>= 
@!accept_scrap: constant eight_bits:=1; {denotes \&{accept}}
@!and_scrap: constant eight_bits:=2; {denotes \&{and}}
@!arrow: constant eight_bits:=3; {denotes `$\KR$'}
@!base: constant eight_bits:=4; {denotes `\#' in based literals}
@!begin_label_scrap: constant eight_bits:=5; {denotes `\.{<<}', i.e.\ the beginning of
 a label}
@!beginning: constant eight_bits:=6; {denotes beginning of block, loop, etc.}
@!case_scrap: constant eight_bits:=7; {denotes \&{case}}
@!clause: constant eight_bits:=8; {denotes a clause in \&{case} statements or
  variant parts, i.e.\ $\&{when}\ldots\KR\null$}
@!close_scrap: constant eight_bits:=9; {denotes a right parenthesis after which 
  indentation ends}
@!colon: constant eight_bits:=10; {denotes a colon}
@!decl: constant eight_bits:=11; {denotes a declaration}
@!digit_scrap: constant eight_bits:=12; {denotes a digit---possibly (in based 
 literals) a character}
@!else_scrap: constant eight_bits:=13; {denotes a quantity starting an else-part}
@!end_label_scrap: constant eight_bits:=14; {denotes `\.{>>}', i.e.\ the ending of
 a label}
@!ending: constant eight_bits:=15; {denotes \&{end}}
@!exception_scrap: constant eight_bits:=16; {denotes \&{exception}}
@!exp: constant eight_bits:=17; {denotes the `\.E' in a real literal}
@!follows: constant eight_bits:=18; {denotes \&{is} and \&{do}}
@!generic_scrap: constant eight_bits:=19; {denotes the beginning of a generic formal
 part}
@!gproc: constant eight_bits:=20; {denotes \&{procedure} and \&{function}
 preceded by \&{with} in a generic formal part}
@!if_scrap: constant eight_bits:=21; {denotes \&{if} and \&{elsif}}
@!in_scrap: constant eight_bits:=22; {denotes \&{in}}
@!label: constant eight_bits:=23; {denotes a complete label}
@!loop_scrap: constant eight_bits:=24; {denotes \&{loop}}
@!math: constant eight_bits:=25; {denotes a quantity to be used in \TeX's 
 math mode only}
@!mod_scrap: constant eight_bits:=26; {denotes a module name}
@!new_scrap: constant eight_bits:=27; {denotes \&{new}}
@!not_scrap: constant eight_bits:=28; {denotes \&{not}}
@!open_scrap: constant eight_bits:=29; {denotes a left parenthesis after which
 indentation begins}
@!period: constant eight_bits:=30; {denotes a `\..'}
@!private_scrap: constant eight_bits:=31; {denotes \&{private}}
@!proc: constant eight_bits:=32; {denotes \&{entry}, \&{function}, etc.}
@!record_scrap: constant eight_bits:=33; {denotes \&{record}}
@!return_scrap: constant eight_bits:=34; {denotes \&{return} and \&{exit}}
@!semi: constant eight_bits:=35; {denotes a semicolon}
@!separate_scrap: constant eight_bits:=36; {denotes \&{separate}}
@!stmt: constant eight_bits:=37; {denotes a statement}
@!terminator: constant eight_bits:=38; {denotes the ending of statements,
 blocks, declaration parts, etc.}
@!then_scrap: constant eight_bits:=39; {denotes \&{then}}
@!when_scrap: constant eight_bits:=40; {denotes \&{when}}
@!with_scrap: constant eight_bits:=41; {denotes \&{use} and \&{with}}
