&\qquad\[D=P\,|indent|\,\pd\,M\,\pd\,|outdent|\,F\,|cancel|\,|indent|]\cr
71&|proc@,math@,follows@,new_scrap| $\RA$ |proc@,math@,math|&instantiation\cr
72&|proc@,math@,follows@,separate_scrap| $\RA$ |proc@,math@,math|&body stub\cr
73&|proc@,math@,semi| $\RA$ |decl|%
  \[D=P\,|indent|\,\pd\,M\,\pd\,|outdent|\,S]&subprogram specification\cr
74&|return_scrap| $\RA$ |math|\[M=\ps\,R\,\sp]&\&{return} with expression\cr
75&|return_scrap@,semi| $\RA$ |stmt|&\&{return};\cr
76&|separate_scrap@,math| $\RA$ |decl|\[D=S\,\pd\,\sp\,M\,\pd]&\&{separate}(\dots)\cr
77&|stmt@,else_scrap@,stmt| $\RA$ |stmt|\[S_3=S_1\,|force|\,|backup|\,E\,
                                     |force|\,S_2]&\&{else} part\cr
78&|stmt@,stmt| $\RA$ |stmt|\[S_3=S_1\,|break_space|\,S_2]&concatenation\cr
79&|stmt@,terminator| $\RA$ |stmt|%
  \[S_2=S_1\,|cancel|\,|outdent|\,|force|\,T\,|force|] &end of block etc.\cr
80&|when_scrap@,math@,arrow| $\RA$ |clause|\[C=W\,\pd\,M\,\pd\,A]
 &clause in \&{case}\cr
81&|with_scrap@,colon| $\RA$ |with_scrap|&\&{use} \&{at}\cr
82&|with_scrap@,math@,semi| $\RA$ |decl|\[D=W\,\pd\,M\,\pd\,S]&context clause\cr
83&|with_scrap@,proc| $\RA$ |gproc|&generic formal subprogram\cr
84&|with_scrap@,record_scrap| $\RA$ |decl|\[D=W\,|indent|\,|force|\,|indent|\,R]
 &\&{record} representation\cr
85&|with_scrap@,record_scrap@,colon| $\RA$ |math@,colon|
&{\it 84\/} with alignment\cr
&\qquad\[M=\pd\,W\,|indent|\,|force|\,|indent|\,R\,\pd]\cr
 }
\yskip\noindent
Translations are not specified here when they are simple concatenations
of the scraps that change. For example, the full translation of
`|colon@,exception_scrap| $\RA$ |colon@,math|' is $C_2=C_1$, $M=E$. The notation
`$\\{digit\_scrap}^*$' which occurs in the productions related to |exp|
(numbers 34 and~35) means a |digit_scrap| scrap that isn't followed by another
|digit_scrap| scrap. 


 
@* Implementing the productions.
When \ADA\ text is to be processed with the grammar above, we put its
initial scraps $s_1\ldots s_n$ into two arrays |cat(1..n)| and |trans(1..n)|.
The value of |cat(k)| is simply a category code from the list above; the
value of |trans(k)| is a text pointer, i.e., an index into |tok_start|.
Our production rules have the nice property that the right-hand side is never
longer than the left-hand side. Therefore it is convenient to use sequential
allocation for the current sequence of scraps. Five pointers are used to
manage the parsing:
 
\yskip\hang |pp| (the parsing pointer) is such that we are trying to match
the category codes |cat(pp)@,cat(pp+1)|$\,\ldots\,$ to the left-hand sides
of productions.
 
\yskip\hang |scrap_base|, |lo_ptr|, |hi_ptr|, and |scrap_ptr| are such that
the current sequence of scraps appears in positions |scrap_base| through
|lo_ptr| and |hi_ptr| through |scrap_ptr|, inclusive, in the |cat| and
|trans| arrays. Scraps located between |scrap_base| and |lo_ptr| have
been examined, while those in positions |>=hi_ptr| have not yet been
looked at by the parsing process.
 
\yskip\noindent Initially |scrap_ptr| is set to the position of the final
scrap to be parsed, and it doesn't change its value. The parsing process
makes sure that |lo_ptr>=pp+4|, since productions have as many as five terms,
by moving scraps from |hi_ptr| to |lo_ptr|. If there are
fewer than |pp+4| scraps left, the positions up to |pp+4| are filled with
blanks that will not match in any productions. Parsing stops when
|pp=lo_ptr+1| and |hi_ptr=scrap_ptr+1|.
 
The |trans| array elements are declared to be of type |0..10_239| instead
of type |text_pointer|, because the final sorting phase of \.{AWEAVE}
uses this array to contain elements of type |name_pointer|. Both
of these types are subranges of |0..10_239|.
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype scrap_index is INTEGER range 0..max_scraps;
type cat_type is array(scrap_index) of eight_bits;
type trans_type is array(scrap_index) of INTEGER range 0..10_239;
@#
@!cat: cat_type;{category codes of scraps}
@!trans: trans_type;{translation texts of scraps}
@!pp:scrap_index; {current position for reducing productions}
@!scrap_base:scrap_index:=1; {beginning of the current scrap sequence}
@!scrap_ptr:scrap_index:=0; {ending of the current scrap sequence}
@!lo_ptr:scrap_index; {last scrap that has been examined}
@!hi_ptr:scrap_index; {first scrap that has not been examined}
stat@!max_scr_ptr:scrap_index:=0; {largest value assumed by |scrap_ptr|}
tats@;
 
@ Token lists in |@!tok_mem| are composed of the following kinds of
items for \TeX\ output.
 
\yskip\item{$\bullet$}ASCII codes and special codes like |force| and
|math_rel| represent themselves;
 
\item{$\bullet$}|id_flag+p| represents \.{\\\\\{{\rm identifier $p$}\}};
 
\item{$\bullet$}|res_flag+p| represents \.{\\\&\{{\rm identifier $p$}\}};
 
\item{$\bullet$}|mod_flag+p| represents module name |p|;
 
\item{$\bullet$}|tok_flag+p| represents token list number |p|;
 
\item{$\bullet$}|inner_tok_flag+p| represents token list number |p|, to be
translated without line-break controls.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!id_flag: constant sixteen_bits:=10_240; {signifies an identifier}
@!res_flag: constant sixteen_bits:=20_480; {signifies a reserved word}
@!mod_flag: constant sixteen_bits:=30_720; {signifies a module name}
@!tok_flag: constant sixteen_bits:=40_960; {signifies a token list}
@!inner_tok_flag: constant sixteen_bits:=51_200;
                                           {signifies a token list in `\ab'}

@ The production rules listed above are embedded directly into the \.{AWEAVE}
program, since it is easier to do this than to write an interpretive system
that would handle production systems in general. Several macros are defined
here so that the program for each production is fairly short.
 
All of our productions conform to the general notion that some |k|
consecutive scraps starting at some position |j| are to be replaced by a
single scrap of some category |c| whose translations is composed from the
translations of the disappearing scraps. After this production has been
applied, the production pointer |pp| should change by an amount |d|. Such
a production can be represented by the quadruple $(j,k,c,d)$. For example,
the production `|math@,math| $\RA$ |math|' would be represented by
`$(|pp|,2,|math|,-3)$'; in this case the pointer $pp$ should decrease by 3
after the production has been applied, because some productions with
|math| in their fourth positions might now match, but no productions have
|math| in the fifth position of their left-hand sides. Note that
the value of |d| is determined by the whole collection of productions, not
by an individual one. 
The determination of |d| has been
done by hand in each case, based on the full set of productions but not on
the grammar of \ADA\ or on the rules for constructing the initial
scraps.
 
Before calling |reduce|, the program should have appended the tokens of
the new translation to the |tok_mem| array. We commonly want to append
copies of several existing translations, and macros are defined to
simplify these common cases. For example, |app2(pp)| will append the
translations of two consecutive scraps, |trans(pp)| and |trans(pp+1)|, to
the current token list. If the entire new translation is formed in this
way, we write `$|squash|(j,k,c,d)$' instead of `$|reduce|(j,k,c,d)$'. For
example, `|squash(pp,2,math,-3)|' is an abbreviation for `|app2(pp);
reduce(pp,2,math,-3)|'.
 
The code below is an exact translation of the production rules into
\ADA, using such macros, and the reader should have no difficulty
understanding the format by comparing the code with the symbolic
productions as they were listed earlier.
 
@d reduce(#)==red(#); goto found@;
@d squash(#)==sq(#); goto found@;
@d app(#)==tok_mem(tok_ptr):=#; incr(tok_ptr)@; {this is like |app_tok|,
  but it doesn't test for overflow}
@d app1(#)==tok_mem(tok_ptr):=tok_flag+trans(#); incr(tok_ptr)@;
@d app2(#)==app1(#);app1(#+1)@;
@d app3(#)==app2(#);app1(#+2)@;
 
@ Let us consider the big case statement for productions now, before looking
at its context. We want to design the program so that this case statement
works, so we might as well not keep ourselves in suspense about exactly what
code needs to be provided with a proper environment.
 
The code here is more complicated than it need be, since some 
compilers are unable to deal with procedures that contain a lot
of program text. The |translate| procedure, which incorporates the \&{case}
statement here, would become too long for those compilers if we did
not do something to split the cases into parts. Therefore
a separate procedure called |do_cases| has been introduced.
@^split procedures@>
 
@<Match a production at |pp|, or increase |pp| if there is no match@>=
if cat(pp)<if_scrap then do_cases;
else
case cat(pp) is
when if_scrap => @+@<Cases for |if_scrap|@>;
when in_scrap => @+@<Cases for |in_scrap|@>;
when label => @+@<Cases for |label|@>;
when loop_scrap => @+@<Cases for |loop_scrap|@>;
when math => @+@<Cases for |math|@>;
when mod_scrap => @+@<Cases for |mod_scrap|@>;
when new_scrap => @+@<Cases for |new_scrap|@>;
when not_scrap => @+@<Cases for |not_scrap|@>;
when open_scrap => @+@<Cases for |open_scrap|@>;
when period => @+@<Cases for |period|@>;
when private_scrap => @+@<Cases for |private_scrap|@>;
when proc => @+@<Cases for |proc|@>;
when return_scrap  => @+@<Cases for |return_scrap|@>;
when separate_scrap => @+@<Cases for |separate_scrap|@>;
when stmt => @+@<Cases for |stmt|@>;
when when_scrap => @+@<Cases for |when_scrap|@>;
when with_scrap => @+@<Cases for |with_scrap|@>;
when others => @+null;
end case;
incr(pp); {if no match was found, we move to the right}
end if;
<<found>> null@;

@ Here is the procedure that need to be present for the reason just
explained.

@<Declaration of subprocedure for |translate|@>=
procedure do_cases is separate;

@
@a
@~do_cases.a@>
@.do_cases.a@>
separate(parsing) procedure @!do_cases is
begin
case cat(pp) is
when accept_scrap => @+@<Cases for |accept_scrap|@>;
when and_scrap  => @+@<Cases  for |and_scrap|@>;
when arrow => @+@<Cases  for |arrow|@>;
when base => @+@<Cases for |base|@>;
when begin_label_scrap => @+@<Cases for |begin_label_scrap|@>;
when beginning => @+@<Cases for |beginning|@>;
when case_scrap => @+@<Cases for |case_scrap|@>;
when clause => @+@<Cases for |clause|@>;
when colon => @+@<Cases  for |colon|@>;
when decl  => @+@<Cases for |decl|@>;
when digit_scrap => @+@<Cases for |digit_scrap|@>;
when else_scrap => @+@<Cases for |else_scrap|@>;
when ending => @+@<Cases for |ending|@>;
when exception_scrap => @+@<Cases for |exception_scrap|@>;
when exp => @+@<Cases for |exp|@>;
when generic_scrap => @+@<Cases for |generic_scrap|@>;
when gproc => @+@<Cases for |gproc|@>;
when others => @+null;
end case;
incr(pp);
<<found>> null;
end do_cases;

@ Now comes the code that tries to match each production that starts
with a particular type of scrap. Whenever a match is discovered,
the |squash| or |reduce| macro will cause the appropriate action
to be performed, followed by |goto found@;|.
 
@<Cases for |accept_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,follows) then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  app(outdent); app1(pp+2);@/ reduce(pp,3,beginning,-2);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1);
  app(pdollar); app1(pp+2);@/ reduce(pp,3,stmt,-3);
end if@;
 
@ @<Cases for |and_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=then_scrap then
  app(@'\'); app(@'A'); app(@'N'); app(@'T');@/ reduce(pp,2,math,-3);
@.\\ANT@>
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |arrow|@>=
squash(pp,1,math,-3)@;

@ @<Cases for |base|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=base then
  app(@'\'); app(@'b'); app(@'n'); app(@'{'); app1(pp);
  app(@'}'); app(@'{'); app1(pp+1); app(@'}');@/ reduce(pp,2,math,-3);
@.\\bn@>
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |begin_label_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,end_label_scrap) then
  app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar); app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,label,-1);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |beginning|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=stmt then
  app(force); app(indent); app1(pp); app(force); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |case_scrap|@>= 
if cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(math,follows,decl) then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app(sspace); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  app(indent); app1(pp+2); app(force); app1(pp+3);
  @/reduce(pp,4,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(math,follows,stmt) then
  app(force); app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app(sspace); app1(pp+1);
  app(pdollar); app(indent); app1(pp+2); app(force); app1(pp+3);
  @/reduce(pp,4,stmt,-3);
end if@;
 
@ @<Cases for |clause|@>=
  if cat(pp+1)=decl then
    app(force); app(backup); app1(pp); app(force); app1(pp+1);
    @/reduce(pp,2,decl,-3);
  elsif cat(pp+1)=stmt then
    app(force); app(backup); app1(pp); app(force); app1(pp+1);
    @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
  end if@;
 
@ @<Cases for |colon|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=exception_scrap then
  squash(pp+1,1,math,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1)=in_scrap then
  app1(pp); app(@'\'); app(@'&'); app(@'{'); app(@'i'); app(@'n'); app(@'}');
  app(sspace); @/reduce(pp,2,colon,-2);
@.\\\&@>
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |decl|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=beginning then
  app1(pp); app(force); app(backup); app1(pp+1); app(force);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=decl then
  app1(pp); app(force); app1(pp+1); @/reduce(pp,2,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(mod_scrap,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(force); app2(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,3,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=terminator then
  app1(pp); app(cancel); app(outdent); app(force); app1(pp+1); app(force);
  @/reduce(pp,2,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=with_scrap then
  app1(pp); app(force); app1(pp+1); @/reduce(pp,2,with_scrap,-1);
end if@;
 

 
@ @<Cases for |digit_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=base then
  app1(pp); @/reduce(pp,2,base,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1)=digit_scrap then
  squash(pp,2,digit_scrap,-2);
elsif cat(pp+1)=period then
  squash(pp,2,digit_scrap,-2);
else
  squash(pp,1,math,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |else_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=else_scrap then
  app(@'\'); app(@'O'); app(@'R'); app(@'E');
  @/reduce(pp,2,math,-3);
@.\\ORE@>
elsif cat(pp+1)=when_scrap then
  app(@'\'); app(@'O'); app(@'R'); app(@'W');
  @/reduce(pp,2,when_scrap,-1);
@.\\ORW@>
end if@;


@
@d compress_end==app1(pp); app(sspace); app2(pp+1)@;

@<Cases for |ending|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(beginning,semi) then
  compress_end;
  @/reduce(pp,3,terminator,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(case_scrap,semi) then
  app(backup); app(outdent); compress_end;
  @/reduce(pp,3,terminator,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(if_scrap,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(sspace); app(outdent); app2(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,3,terminator,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(loop_scrap,semi) then
  compress_end;
  @/reduce(pp,3,terminator,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(loop_scrap,math,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(sspace); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  app(sspace); app1(pp+2); app(pdollar); app1(pp+3);
  @/reduce(pp,4,terminator,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(pdollar); app(sspace); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,terminator,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(record_scrap,semi) then
  app(outdent); compress_end;
  @/reduce(pp,3,terminator,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1)=semi then
  squash(pp,2,terminator,-1);
end if@;
 
@ @<Cases for |exception_scrap|@>=
app(backup); app1(pp);
@/reduce(pp,1,beginning,-2)@;

@ @<Cases for |exp|@>=
if (cat(pp+1)=digit_scrap) and (cat(pp+2)/=digit_scrap) then
  app2(pp); app(@'}');
  @/reduce(pp,2,math,-3);
elsif (cat(pp+1)=math) and ((cat(pp+2)=digit_scrap) and (cat(pp+3)/=digit_scrap)) then
  app3(pp); app(@'}');
  @/reduce(pp,3,math,-3);
end if @;
  
@ @<Cases for |generic_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=decl then
 app1(pp); app(force); app1(pp+1);
 @/reduce(pp,2,generic_scrap,0);
elsif cat(pp+1)=proc then
 app(indent); app1(pp); app(outdent);
 app(force); app1(pp+1);
 @/reduce(pp,2,proc,-1);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |gproc|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  app(outdent); app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+4)=(math,follows,math,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app3(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  app(outdent); app1(pp+4);
  @/reduce(pp,5,decl,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |if_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(math,then_scrap,stmt) then
  app(force); app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app(sspace); app1(pp+1);
  app(pdollar); app(outdent); app1(pp+2); app(force); app1(pp+3);
  @/reduce(pp,4,stmt,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |in_scrap|@>=
  squash(pp,1,math,-3)@;

@ @<Cases for |label|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=label then
  app1(pp); app(sspace); app(opt); app(@'7'); app(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,label,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1)=stmt then
  app(force); app(backup); app1(pp); app(sspace); app(cancel); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
end if@;
 

@ @<Cases for |loop_scrap|@>=
  squash(pp,1,beginning,-2)@;


@ @<Cases for |math|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(and_scrap,math) then
  squash(pp,3,math,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(colon,beginning) then
  app(backup); app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(sspace); app(pdollar);
  app1(pp+1); app(sspace); app1(pp+2); @/reduce(pp,3,beginning,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(colon,decl) then
  app(force); app(backup); app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(sspace); app(pdollar);
  app1(pp+1); app(sspace); app(cancel); app1(pp+2); @/reduce(pp,3,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(colon,math,semi) then
  app(pdollar); app3(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+3); 
  @/reduce(pp,4,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(else_scrap,math) then
  app1(pp); app(@'\'); app(@'V'); app1(pp+2);
@.\\V@>
  @/reduce(pp,3,math,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(follows,math,semi) then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  app1(pp+2); app(pdollar); app1(pp+3); @/reduce(pp,4,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(follows,record_scrap) then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(indent); app(force);
  app1(pp+2); app(indent); app(force); @/reduce(pp,3,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=loop_scrap then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(pdollar); app(sspace); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,beginning,-2);
elsif cat(pp+1)=math then
  squash(pp,2,math,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=semi then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=stmt then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=separate_scrap then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,separate_scrap,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(when_scrap,math) then
  squash(pp,3,math,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=with_scrap then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(pspace); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,with_scrap,-1);
end if@;
 
@ @<Cases for |mod_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=semi then 
  app2(pp); app(force);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
else
  squash(pp,1,math,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |new_scrap|@>=
  squash(pp,1,math,-3)@;

@ @<Cases for |not_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=in_scrap then
  app(@'\'); app(@'n'); app(@'o'); app(@'t'); app(@'i'); app(@'n');
@.\\notin@>
  @/reduce(pp,2,math,-3);
else
  squash(pp,1,math,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |open_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=decl then
  app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar); app(@'\'); app(@','); 
  app(opt); app(@'5');
@.\\,@>
  @/reduce(pp,2,open_scrap,0);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,close_scrap) then
  app(indent); app2(pp); app(outdent); app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,math,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+4)=(math,colon,math,close_scrap) then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app3(pp+1);
  app(outdent); app1(pp+4);
  @/reduce(pp,5,math,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |period|@>=
  squash(pp,1,math,-3)@;

@ @<Cases for |private_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=semi then
  squash(pp,1,math,-2);
else
  app(force); app(backup); app1(pp); app(force);
  @/reduce(pp,1,decl,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |proc|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(math,follows,new_scrap) then
  squash(pp+2,2,math,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+3)=(math,follows,separate_scrap) then
  squash(pp+2,2,math,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,follows) then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1);
  app(pdollar); app(outdent); app1(pp+2); app(cancel); app(indent);
  @/reduce(pp,3,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1);
  app(pdollar); app(outdent); app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,decl,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |return_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=semi then
 squash(pp,2,stmt,-3);
else
 app(pspace); app1(pp); app(sspace);
 @/reduce(pp,1,math,-3);
end if@;

@ @<Cases for |separate_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=math then
  app1(pp); app(pdollar); app(sspace); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar);
  @/reduce(pp,2,decl,-3);
end if@;
 
@ @<Cases for |stmt|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(else_scrap,stmt) then
  app1(pp); app(force); app(backup); app1(pp+1); app(force); app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,stmt,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=stmt then
  app1(pp); app(break_space); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=terminator then
  app1(pp); app(cancel); app(outdent); app(force); app1(pp+1); app(force);
  @/reduce(pp,2,stmt,-3);
end if@;
  
@ @<Cases for |when_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,arrow) then
  app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar); app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,clause,-1);
end if@;
 
@ @<Cases for |with_scrap|@>=
if cat(pp+1)=colon then
  squash(pp,2,with_scrap,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(math,semi) then
  app1(pp); app(pdollar); app1(pp+1); app(pdollar); app1(pp+2);
  @/reduce(pp,3,decl,-3);
elsif cat(pp+1)=proc then
  squash(pp,2,gproc,0);
elsif cat(pp+1..pp+2)=(record_scrap,colon) then
  app(pdollar); app1(pp); app(indent); app(force); app(indent); app1(pp+1);
  app(pdollar);
  @/reduce(pp,2,math,-1);
elsif cat(pp+1)=record_scrap then
  app1(pp); app(indent); app(force); app(indent); app1(pp+1);
  @/reduce(pp,2,decl,-3);
end if@;

 
@ The `|freeze_text|' macro is used to give official status to a token list.
Before saying |freeze_text|, items are appended to the current token list,
and we know that the eventual number of this token list will be the current
value of |text_ptr|. But no list of that number really exists as yet,
because no ending point for the current list has been
stored in the |tok_start| array. After saying |freeze_text|, the
old current token list becomes legitimate, and its number is the current
value of |text_ptr-1| since |text_ptr| has been increased. The new
current token list is empty and ready to be appended to.
Note that |freeze_text| does not check to see that |text_ptr| hasn't gotten
too large, since it is assumed that this test was done beforehand.
 
@d freeze_text==incr(text_ptr); tok_start(text_ptr):=tok_ptr@;
 
@ The `|reduce|' macro used in our code for productions actually calls on
a procedure named `|red|', which makes the appropriate changes to the
scrap list.
 
@<Procedures in |pars...@>=
procedure @!red(@!j:sixteen_bits; @!k:eight_bits; @!c:eight_bits;
  @!d:INTEGER)is
begin cat(j):=c; trans(j):=text_ptr; freeze_text;
if k>1 then
  for i in j+k..lo_ptr loop
    cat(i-k+1):=cat(i); trans(i-k+1):=trans(i);
  end loop;
  lo_ptr:=lo_ptr-k+1;
end if;
@<Change |pp| to $\max(|scrap_base|,|pp+d|)$@>;
end red;
 
@ @<Change |pp| to $\max(|scrap_base|,|pp+d|)$@>=
if pp+d>=scrap_base then pp:=pp+d;
else pp:=scrap_base;
end if@;
 
@ Similarly, the `|squash|' macro invokes a procedure called `|sq|'. This
procedure takes advantage of the simplification that occurs when |k=1|.
 
@<Procedures in |pars...@>=
procedure @!sq(@!j:sixteen_bits; @!k:eight_bits; @!c:eight_bits;
  @!d:INTEGER)is
begin if k=1 then
  cat(j):=c; @/
  @<Change |pp|...@>;
else  for i in j..j+k-1 loop
    app1(i);
    end loop;
  red(j,k,c,d);
  end if;
end sq;
 
@ Here now is the code that applies productions as long as possible. 
 
@<Reduce the scraps using the productions until no more rules apply@>=
loop @<Make sure the entries |cat(pp..pp+4)| are defined@>;
  if (tok_ptr+11>max_toks)or(text_ptr+4>max_texts) then
    stat if tok_ptr>max_tok_ptr then max_tok_ptr:=tok_ptr; end if;
    if text_ptr>max_txt_ptr then max_txt_ptr:=text_ptr; end if;
    tats@;
    overflow("token/text");
    end if;
  exit when pp>lo_ptr;@/ 
  @<Match a production...@>;
  end loop@;

 
@ If we get to the end of the scrap list, category codes equal to zero are
stored, since zero does not match anything in a production.
 
@<Make sure the entries...@>=
if lo_ptr<pp+4 then
  loop if hi_ptr<=scrap_ptr then
    incr(lo_ptr);@/
    cat(lo_ptr):=cat(hi_ptr); trans(lo_ptr):=trans(hi_ptr);@/
    incr(hi_ptr);
    end if;
  exit when (hi_ptr>scrap_ptr)or(lo_ptr=pp+4);
  end loop;
  for i in lo_ptr+1..pp+4 loop cat(i):=0; end loop;
end if@;
 
@ The |translate| function assumes that scraps have been stored in
positions |scrap_base| through |scrap_ptr| of |cat| and |trans|. It
appends a |comment_scrap| and begins to apply productions as much as
possible. The result is a token list containing the translation of
the given sequence of scraps.
 
After calling |translate|, we will have |text_ptr+3<=max_texts| and
|tok_ptr+6<=max_toks|, so it will be possible to create up to three token
lists with up to six tokens without checking for overflow. Before calling
|translate|, we should have |text_ptr<max_texts| and |scrap_ptr<max_scraps|,
since |translate| might add a new text and a new scrap before it checks
for overflow.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |pars...@>=
  function translate return text_pointer;

@ @<Procedures in |pars...@>=
@<Declaration of subproced...@>@;
function translate return text_pointer is separate;

@
@a
@~translate.a@>
@.translate.a@>
separate(parsing) function @!translate return text_pointer is {converts a sequence of scraps}
@!k:long_buffer_index; {index into |buffer|}
begin pp:=scrap_base; lo_ptr:=pp-1; hi_ptr:=pp;
@<Reduce the scraps...@>;
if (lo_ptr=scrap_base)and(cat(lo_ptr)/=math) then return trans(lo_ptr);
else @<Combine the irreducible scraps that remain@>;
end if;
end translate;
 
@ If the initial sequence of scraps does not reduce to a single scrap,
we concatenate the translations of all remaining scraps, separated by
blank spaces, with dollar signs surrounding the translations of |math|
scraps.
 
@<Combine the irreducible...@>=
for j in scrap_base..lo_ptr loop
  if j/=scrap_base then
    app(@' ');
  end if;
  if cat(j)=math or cat(j)=open_scrap or cat(j)=close_scrap then
    app(pdollar);
  end if;
  app1(j);
  if cat(j)=math or cat(j)=open_scrap or cat(j)=close_scrap then
    app(pdollar);
  end if;
  if tok_ptr+6>max_toks then overflow("token"); end if;
  end loop;
freeze_text; return text_ptr-1@;
 
@* Initializing the scraps.
If we are going to use the powerful production mechanism just developed, we
must get the scraps set up in the first place, given a \ADA\ text. A table
of the initial scraps corresponding to \ADA\ tokens appeared above in the
section on parsing; our goal now is to implement that table. We shall do this
by implementing a subroutine called |ADA_parse| that is analogous to the
|ADA_xref| routine used during phase one.
 
Like |ADA_xref|, the |ADA_parse| procedure starts with the current
value of |next_control| and it uses the operation |next_control:=get_next@;|
repeatedly to read \ADA\ text until encountering the next `\v' or
`\.\{', or until |next_control>=format|. The scraps corresponding to what
it reads are appended into the |cat| and |trans| arrays, and |scrap_ptr|
is advanced.
 
Like |prod|, this procedure has to split into pieces so that each
part is short enough to be handled by \ADA\ compilers that discriminate
against long subroutines. This time there is one split-off routine,
called |easy_cases|.
@^split procedures@>
 
After studying |ADA_parse|, we will look at the sub-procedure
|app_comment|, that is used in some of its branches.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |pars...@>=
  procedure app_comment;

@ @<Procedures in |pars...@>=
@<Declaration of the |app_comment| procedure@>@;
@<Declaration of the |easy_cases| procedure@>@;
procedure ADA_parse is separate;

@
@a
@~ada_parse.a@>
@.ada_parse.a@>
separate(parsing)
procedure @!ADA_parse is {creates scraps from \ADA\ tokens}
@!j:long_buffer_index; {index into |buffer|}
@!p:name_pointer; {identifier designator}
begin while next_control<format loop
  @<Append the scrap appropriate to |next_control|@>;
  next_control:=get_next;
  if (next_control=@'|')or(next_control=@'{') then return; end if;
  end loop;
end ADA_parse;
 
@ The macros defined here are helpful abbreviations for the operations
needed when generating the scraps. A scrap of category |c| whose
translation has three tokens $t_1$, $t_2$, $t_3$ is generated by
|sc3|$(t_1)(t_2)(t_3)(c)$, etc.
 
@d s0(#)==incr(scrap_ptr); cat(scrap_ptr):=#; trans(scrap_ptr):=text_ptr;
  freeze_text@;
@d sc1(#)==app(#);s0@;
@d sc2(#)==app(#);sc1@;
@d sc3(#)==app(#);sc2@;
@d sc4(#)==app(#);sc3@;
@d sc5(#)==app(#);sc4@;
@d sc6(#)==app(#);sc5@;
@d sc0(#)==incr(scrap_ptr); cat(scrap_ptr):=#; trans(scrap_ptr):=0@;
@d comment_scrap(#)==app(#); app_comment@;

 
@ @<Append the scr...@>=
@<Make sure that there is room for at least four more scraps, six more
tokens, and four more texts@>;
<<reswitch>> case next_control is
when str ! verbatim ! output_tok ! character_tok =>
            @+@<Append \(a \(string scrap@>;
when ascii_tok => @+@<Append \(an ASCII-token scrap@>;
when identifier => @+@<Append \(an identifier scrap@>;
when TeX_string => @+@<Append \(a \TeX\ string scrap@>;
when others => @+easy_cases;
end case@;
 
@ The |easy_cases| each result in straightforward scraps.
 
@<Declaration of the |easy_cases| procedure@>=
procedure @!easy_cases is {a subprocedure of |ADA_parse|}
begin case next_control is
when set_element_sign => @+sc3(@'\')(@'i')(@'n')(in_scrap);
@.\\in@>
when double_dot => @+sc3(@'\')(@'t')(@'o')(math);
when @'#' ! @'$' ! @'%' ! @'^' ! @'_' =>
     @+sc4(pdollar)(@'\')(next_control)(pdollar)(math);
@.\\to@>
@.\\\#@>
@.\\\$@>
@.\\\%@>
@.\\\^@>
@.\\_@>
when @'&' => @+sc6(math_bin)(@'\')(@'.')(@'\')(@'&')(@'}')(math);
@.\&@>
when @'!' => @+sc5(math_rel)(@'\')(@'.')(@'|')(@'}')(math);
@.!@>
@.|@>
when ignore ! @'|' ! xref_roman..xref_reserved => @+null;
when @'(' => @+sc1(next_control)(open_scrap);
when @')' => @+sc1(next_control)(close_scrap);
when @'*' => @+sc4(@'\')(@'a')(@'s')(@'t')(math);
@.\\ast@>
when @',' => @+sc3(@',')(opt)(@'9')(math);
when @'0'..@'9' => if (buffer(loc)=@'#')or(buffer(loc+1)=@'#') then
                     @<Get a based number@>;
                   else
                     sc3(pdollar)(next_control)(pdollar)(digit_scrap);
                   end if;
when @'.' => @+sc1(@'.')(period);
when @';' => @+sc1(@';')(semi);
when @':' => @+sc1(@':')(colon);
@/@t\4@>@<Cases involving nonstandard ASCII characters@>@;
when exponent => @+sc3(@'\')(@'E')(@'{')(exp);
@.\\E@>
when begin_comment => @+sc2(@'\')(@'B')(math);
@.\\B@>
when end_comment => @+sc2(@'\')(@'T')(math);
@.\\T@>
when force_line => @+sc2(@'\')(@')')(math);
@.\\)@>
when thin_space => @+sc2(@'\')(@',')(math);
@.\\,@>
when math_break => @+sc2(opt)(@'0')(math);
when line_break => @+comment_scrap(force);
when big_line_break => @+comment_scrap(big_force);
when no_line_break => @+app(big_cancel); app(@'\'); app(@'8');
@.\\8@>
  comment_scrap(big_cancel);
when pseudo_semi => @+sc0(semi);
when join => @+sc2(@'\')(@'J')(math);
@.\\J@>
when others => @+sc1(next_control)(math);
end case;
end easy_cases;
 
@ @<Get a based...@>=
@<Append \(|digit_scrap| scraps until a `\#' occurs@>;
sc1(next_control)(base);
next_control:=get_next;@/
@<Append \(|digit_scrap|...@>;
sc1(next_control)(base)@;

@ @<Append \(|digit_scrap|...@>=
loop
if next_control=@'_' then
  sc2(@'\')(@'_')(digit_scrap);
@.\\_@>
else
  sc1(next_control)(digit_scrap);
end if;
next_control:=get_next;@/
exit when next_control=@'#';
end loop@;

@ @<Make sure that there is room for at least four...@>=
if (scrap_ptr+4>max_scraps)or(tok_ptr+6>max_toks)or(text_ptr+4>max_texts) then
  stat if scrap_ptr>max_scr_ptr then max_scr_ptr:=scrap_ptr; end if;
  if tok_ptr>max_tok_ptr then max_tok_ptr:=tok_ptr; end if;
  if text_ptr>max_txt_ptr then max_txt_ptr:=text_ptr; end if;
  tats@;
  overflow("scrap/token/text");
  end if@;
 
@ Some nonstandard ASCII characters may have entered \.{AWEAVE} by means of
standard ones. They are converted to \TeX\ control sequences so that it is
possible to keep \.{AWEAVE} from stepping beyond standard ASCII.
 
@<Cases involving nonstandard...@>=
when not_equal => @+sc2(@'\')(@'I')(math);
@.\\I@>
when less_or_equal => @+sc2(@'\')(@'L')(math);
@.\\L@>
when greater_or_equal => @+sc2(@'\')(@'G')(math);
@.\\G@>
when equivalence_sign => @+sc2(@'\')(@'S')(math);
@.\\S@>
when and_sign => @+sc2(@'\')(@'W')(and_scrap);
@.\\W@>
when or_sign => @+sc2(@'\')(@'V')(else_scrap);
@.\\V@>
when not_sign => @+sc2(@'\')(@'R')(not_scrap);
@.\\R@>
when left_arrow => @+sc2(@'\')(@'K')(math);
@.\\K@>
when right_arrow => @+sc3(@'\')(@'K')(@'R')(arrow);
@.\\KR@>
when double_star => @+sc4(@'\')(@'d')(@'s')(@'t')(math);
@.\\dst@>
when left_label_bracket => @+sc3(@'\')(@'B')(@'L')(begin_label_scrap);
@.\\BL@>
when right_label_bracket => @+sc3(@'\')(@'E')(@'L')(end_label_scrap);
@.\\EL@>
when box_sign => @+sc4(@'\')(@'B')(@'O')(@'X')(math);
@.\\BOX@>


 
@ The following code must use |app_tok| instead of |app| in order to
protect against overflow. Note that |tok_ptr+1<=max_toks| after |app_tok|
has been used, so another |app| is legitimate before testing again.
 
Many of the special characters in a string must be prefixed by `\.\\' so that
\TeX\ will print them properly.
@^special string characters@>
 
@<Append \(a \(string scrap@>=
app(pdollar); app(@'\');
case next_control is
when verbatim => @+app(@'=');
@.\\=@>
when output_tok => @+app(@'O');
@.\\O@>
when others => @+app(@'.');
@.\\.@>
end case;
app(@'{'); j:=id_first;
while j<id_loc loop
  @<Append the character appropriate to |buffer(j)|@>;
  incr(j);
  end loop;
if next_control=output_tok then
  sc3(@'}')(pdollar)(force)(math);
else
  sc2(@'}')(pdollar)(math);
end if@;

@ @<Append the character...@>=
  case buffer(j) is
    when @' ' ! @'\' ! @'%' ! @'$' ! @'^' ! @''' ! @'`' ! @'{' !
         @'#' ! @'}' ! @'~' ! @'&' ! @'_' => app(@'\');
@.\\\ @>
@.\\\\@>
@.\\\#@>
@.\\\%@>
@.\\\$@>
@.\\\^@>
@.\\'@>
@.\\`@>
@.\\\{@>
@.\\\}@>
@.\\\~@>
@.\\\&@>
@.\\_@>
    when @'@@' => if buffer(j+1)=@'@@' then incr(j);
      else
  err_print("! Double @@ should be used in strings and character literals");
@.Double \AT! should be used...@>
      end if;
    when others => null;
  end case;
  app_tok(buffer(j))@;

@ @<Append \(an ASCII...@>=
app(pdollar); app(@'\'); app(@'H'); app(@'{');
@.\\H@>
j:=id_first+1; @<Append the character...@>;
sc2(@'}')(pdollar)(math)@;

@ @<Append \(a \TeX\ string scrap@>=
app(pdollar); app(@'\'); app(@'h'); app(@'b'); app(@'o'); app(@'x');
app(@'{');
@.\\hbox@>
for l in id_first..id_loc-1 loop app_tok(buffer(l)); end loop;
sc2(@'}')(pdollar)(math)@;
 
@ @<Append \(an identifier scrap@>=
p:=id_lookup(normal);
case ilk(p) is
when normal ! predefined  => 
     @+sc5(pspace)(pdollar)(id_flag+p)(pdollar)(pspace)(math);
                    {not a reserved word}
when accept_like => @+sc2(res_flag+p)(sspace)(accept_scrap);
when all_like    => @+sc5(pdollar)(pspace)(res_flag+p)(pdollar)(pspace)(math);
when and_like    => @+sc2(@'\')(@'W')(and_scrap);
@.\\W@>
when array_like  => @+sc2(res_flag+p)(sspace)(open_scrap);
when at_like     => @+sc3(sspace)(res_flag+p)(sspace)(colon);
when begin_like  => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(beginning);
when body_like   => @+sc4(pdollar)(res_flag+p)(pdollar)(pspace)(math);
when case_like   => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(case_scrap);
when declare_like => @+sc4(force)(res_flag+p)(indent)(force)(decl);
when goto_like    => @+sc5(pspace)(pdollar)(res_flag+p)(pdollar)(sspace)(math);
when is_like      => @+sc3(sspace)(res_flag+p)(sspace)(follows);
when else_like    => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(else_scrap);
when elsif_like   => @+sc2(backup)(res_flag+p)(if_scrap);
when end_like     => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(ending);
when exception_like => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(exception_scrap);
when proc_like    => @+sc2(res_flag+p)(sspace)(proc);
when new_like     => @+sc3(pspace)(res_flag+p)(pspace)(new_scrap);
when generic_like => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(generic_scrap);
when if_like      => @+sc2(res_flag+p)(indent)(if_scrap);
when in_like      => @+sc3(@'\')(@'i')(@'n')(in_scrap);
@.\\in@>
when loop_like    => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(loop_scrap);
when mod_like     => @+sc3(math_bin)(res_flag+p)(@'}')(math);
when not_like     => @+sc2(@'\')(@'R')(not_scrap);
@.\\R@>
when of_like      => @+sc3(sspace)(res_flag+p)(sspace)(close_scrap); 
when or_like      => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(else_scrap);
when pragma_like  => @+sc2(res_flag+p)(sspace)(proc);
when private_like => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(private_scrap);
when range_like   => @+sc5(sspace)(pdollar)(res_flag+p)(pdollar)(sspace)(math);
when record_like  => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(record_scrap);
when return_like  => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(return_scrap);
when separate_like => @+sc1(res_flag+p)(separate_scrap);
when type_like     => @+sc4(pdollar)(res_flag+p)(pdollar)(sspace)(math);
when then_like     => @+sc2(sspace)(res_flag+p)(then_scrap);
when with_like     => @+sc3(pspace)(res_flag+p)(sspace)(with_scrap);
when when_like     => @+sc2(res_flag+p)(sspace)(when_scrap);
when others => @+null;
end case@;

@ A comment is incorporated into the previous scrap.
The |app_comment| procedure takes care of placing a comment at the end of the
current scrap list. When |app_comment| is called, we assume that the current
token list is the translation of the comment involved.
 
@<Declaration of the |app_comment|...@>=
procedure @!app_comment is {append a comment to the scrap list}
begin freeze_text;
app1(scrap_ptr);
app(text_ptr-1+tok_flag); trans(scrap_ptr):=text_ptr; freeze_text;
end app_comment;
 
@ When the `\v' that introduces \ADA\ text is sensed, a call on
|ADA_translate| will return a pointer to the \TeX\ translation of
that text. If scraps exist in the |cat| and |trans| arrays, they are
unaffected by this translation process.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |pars...@>=
  function ADA_translate return text_pointer;

@ @<Procedures in |pars...@>=
function @!ADA_translate return text_pointer is
@!p:text_pointer; {points to the translation}
@!save_base:scrap_index; {holds original value of |scrap_base|}
begin save_base:=scrap_base; scrap_base:=scrap_ptr+1;
ADA_parse; {get the scraps together}
if next_control/=@'|' then err_print("! Missing `|' after ADA text");
@.Missing `|'...@>
end if;
app_tok(cancel); app_comment; {place a |cancel| token as a final ``comment''}
p:=translate; {make the translation}
stat if scrap_ptr>max_scr_ptr then max_scr_ptr:=scrap_ptr;end if; tats@;
scrap_ptr:=scrap_base-1; scrap_base:=save_base; {scrap the scraps}
return p;
end ADA_translate;
 
@ The |outer_parse| routine is to |ADA_parse| as |outer_xref|
is to |ADA_xref|: It constructs a sequence of scraps for \ADA\ text
until |next_control>=format|. Thus, it takes care of embedded comments.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |pars...@>=
  procedure outer_parse;

@ @<Procedures in |pars...@>=
procedure @!outer_parse is {makes scraps from \ADA\ tokens and comments}
@!bal:eight_bits; {brace level in comment}
@!p,@!q:text_pointer; {partial comments}
begin while next_control<format loop
  if next_control/=@'{' then ADA_parse;
  else  @<Make sure that there is room for at least seven more
      tokens, three more texts, and one more scrap@>;
    app(@'\'); app(@'C'); app(@'{');
@.\\C@>
    bal:=copy_comment(1); next_control:=@'|';
    while bal>0 loop
      p:=text_ptr; freeze_text; q:=ADA_translate;
      {at this point we have |tok_ptr+6<=max_toks|}
      app(tok_flag+p); app(inner_tok_flag+q);
      if next_control=@'|' then bal:=copy_comment(bal);
      else bal:=0; {an error has been reported}
      end if;
      end loop;
    app(force); app_comment; {the full comment becomes a scrap}
    end if;
  end loop;
end outer_parse;
 
@ @<Make sure that there is room for at least seven more...@>=
if (tok_ptr+7>max_toks)or(text_ptr+3>max_texts)or(scrap_ptr>=max_scraps) then
  stat if scrap_ptr>max_scr_ptr then max_scr_ptr:=scrap_ptr; end if;
  if tok_ptr>max_tok_ptr then max_tok_ptr:=tok_ptr; end if;
  if text_ptr>max_txt_ptr then max_txt_ptr:=text_ptr; end if;
  tats@;
  overflow("token/text/scrap");
  end if@;
 
@* Output of tokens.
So far our programs have only built up multi-layered token lists in
\.{AWEAVE}'s internal memory; we have to figure out how to get them into
the desired final form. The job of converting token lists to characters in
the \TeX\ output file is not difficult, although it is an implicitly
recursive process. Three main considerations had to be kept in mind when
this part of \.{AWEAVE} was designed:  (a) There are two modes of output,
|outer| mode that translates tokens like |force| into line-breaking
control sequences, and |inner| mode that ignores them except that blank
spaces take the place of line breaks. (b) The |cancel| instruction applies
to adjacent token or tokens that are output, and this cuts across levels
of recursion since `|cancel|' occurs at the beginning or end of a token
list on one level. (c) The \TeX\ output file will be semi-readable if line
breaks are inserted after the result of tokens like |break_space| and
|force|.  (d) The final line break should be suppressed, and there should
be no |force| token output immediately after `\.{\\Y\\P}'.
 
@ The output process uses a stack to keep track of what is going on at
different ``levels'' as the token lists are being written out. Entries on
this stack have three parts:
 
\yskip\hang |end_field| is the |tok_mem| location where the token list of a
particular level will end;
 
\yskip\hang |tok_field| is the |tok_mem| location from which the next token
on a particular level will be read;
 
\yskip\hang |mode_field| is the current mode, either |inner| or |outer|.
 
\yskip\noindent The current values of these quantities are referred to
quite frequently, so they are stored in a separate place instead of in the
|stack| array. We call the current values |cur_end|, |cur_tok|, and
|cur_mode|.
 
The global variable |stack_ptr| tells how many levels of output are
currently in progress. The end of output occurs when an |end_translation|
token is found, so the stack is never empty except when we first begin the
output process.
 
@d init_stack==stack_ptr:=0;cur_mode:=outer@; 
                                           {do this to initialize the stack}
 
@<Types...@>=
type output_mode is (@!inner,@!outer);
type output_state is record@!end_field:sixteen_bits; {ending location of token list}
  @!tok_field:sixteen_bits; {present location within token list}
  @!mode_field:output_mode; {interpretation of control tokens}
  end record;
@# 
@!cur_state:output_state; {|cur_end|, |cur_tok|, |cur_mode|}
@!stack:array(INTEGER range 1..stack_size) of output_state; {info for non-current levels}
@!stack_ptr:INTEGER range 0..stack_size; {first unused location in the output state stack}
stat@!max_stack_ptr:INTEGER range 0..stack_size:=0; 
                                       {largest value assumed by |stack_ptr|}
tats@;
@# 
@!cur_end: sixteen_bits renames cur_state.end_field; 
                                      {current ending location in |tok_mem|}
@!cur_tok: sixteen_bits renames cur_state.tok_field; 
                                {location of next output token in |tok_mem|}
@!cur_mode: output_mode renames cur_state.mode_field;
                                            {current mode of interpretation}
 

@ To insert token-list |p| into the output, the |push_level| subroutine
is called; it saves the old level of output and gets a new one going.
The value of |cur_mode| is not changed.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |second...@>=
procedure push_level(p:text_pointer);

@ @<Procedures in |second...@>=
procedure @!push_level(@!p:text_pointer) is {suspends the current level}
begin if stack_ptr=stack_size then overflow("stack");
else  if stack_ptr>0 then
    stack(stack_ptr):=cur_state; {save |cur_end|$\,\ldots\,$|cur_mode|}
    end if;
  incr(stack_ptr);
  stat if stack_ptr>max_stack_ptr then
    max_stack_ptr:=stack_ptr; end if; tats@;
  cur_tok:=tok_start(p); cur_end:=tok_start(p+1);
  end if;
end push_level;
 
@ Conversely, the |pop_level| routine restores the conditions that were in
force when the current level was begun. This subroutine will never be
called when |stack_ptr=1|. It is so simple, we declare it as a macro:
 
@d pop_level==decr(stack_ptr); cur_state:=stack(stack_ptr)@;
  {do this when |cur_tok| reaches |cur_end|}
 
@ The |get_output| function returns the next byte of output that is not a
reference to a token list. It returns the values |identifier| or |res_word|
or |mod_name| if the next token is to be an identifier (typeset in
italics), a reserved word (typeset in boldface) or a module name (typeset
by a complex routine that might generate additional levels of output).
In these cases |cur_name| points to the identifier or module name in
question.

@<Types...@>= 
@!res_word: constant eight_bits:=8#201#; 
                                {returned by |get_output| for reserved words}
@!mod_name: constant eight_bits:=8#200#; 
                                  {returned by |get_output| for module names}

@ @<Procedures in |second...@>=
function @!get_output return eight_bits is {returns the next token of output}
@!a:sixteen_bits; {current item read from |tok_mem|}
begin <<restart>> while cur_tok=cur_end loop pop_level; end loop;
a:=tok_mem(cur_tok); incr(cur_tok);
if a>=8#400# then
  cur_name:=a mod id_flag;
  case a/id_flag is
  when 2 => @+a:=res_word; {|a=res_flag+cur_name|}
  when 3 => @+a:=mod_name; {|a=mod_flag+cur_name|}
  when 4 => @+push_level(cur_name); goto restart; {|a=tok_flag+cur_name|}
  when 5 => @+push_level(cur_name); cur_mode:=inner; goto restart;
            {|a=inner_tok_flag+cur_name|}
  when others => @+a:=identifier; {|a=id_flag+cur_name|}
  end case;
  end if;
return a;
end get_output;
 
@ The real work associated with token output is done by |make_output|.
This procedure appends an |end_translation| token to the current token list,
and then it repeatedly calls |get_output| and feeds characters to the output
buffer until reaching the |end_translation| sentinel. It is possible for
|make_output| to
be called recursively, since a module name may include embedded \ADA\
text; however, the depth of recursion never exceeds one level, since
module names cannot be inside of module names.
 
A procedure called |output_ADA| does the scanning, translation, and
output of \ADA\ text within `\ab' brackets, and this procedure uses
|make_output| to output the current token list. Thus, the recursive call
of |make_output| actually occurs when |make_output| calls |output_ADA|
while outputting the name of a module.
@^recursion@>

@<Specification of procedures visible from |sec...@>=
  procedure make_output;

@ @<Procedures in |second...@>=
procedure @!output_ADA is {outputs the current token list}
@!save_tok_ptr,@!save_text_ptr,@!save_next_control:sixteen_bits;
  {values to be restored}
p:text_pointer; {translation of the \ADA\ text}
begin save_tok_ptr:=tok_ptr; save_text_ptr:=text_ptr;
save_next_control:=next_control; next_control:=@'|'; p:=ADA_translate;
app(p+inner_tok_flag);
make_output; {output the list}
stat if text_ptr>max_txt_ptr then max_txt_ptr:=text_ptr; end if;
if tok_ptr>max_tok_ptr then max_tok_ptr:=tok_ptr; end if; tats@;
text_ptr:=save_text_ptr; tok_ptr:=save_tok_ptr; {forget the tokens}
next_control:=save_next_control; {restore |next_control| to original state}
end output_ADA;
 
@ Here is \.{AWEAVE}'s major output handler.
 
@<Procedures in |second...@>=
procedure @!make_output is {outputs the equivalents of tokens}
@!a:eight_bits; {current output byte}
@!b:eight_bits; {next output byte}
@!k,@!k_limit:byte_index; {indices into |byte_mem|}
@!w:w_range; {row of |byte_mem|}
@!j:long_buffer_index; {index into |buffer|}
@!d:INTEGER; {counts consecutive |@'$'| signs or spaces}
@!string_delimiter:ASCII_code; {first and last character of
  string being copied}
@!save_loc,@!save_limit:long_buffer_index; {|loc| and |limit| to be restored}
@!cur_mod_name:name_pointer; {name of module being output}
@!save_mode:output_mode; {value of |cur_mode| before a sequence of breaks}
@!ignore_spaces:BOOLEAN; {should spaces be ignored?}
begin app(end_translation); {append a sentinel}
freeze_text; push_level(text_ptr-1);
loop  a:=get_output; ignore_spaces:=FALSE;
<<reswitch>> case a is
  when end_translation => return;
  when identifier ! res_word => @<Output an identifier@>;
  when mod_name => @<Output a module name@>;
  when math_bin ! math_op ! math_rel => @<Output a \.{\\math} operator@>;
  when cancel =>  loop a:=get_output;@/
                    exit when (a<backup)or(a>big_force);
                  end loop;
                  ignore_spaces:=FALSE;
                  goto reswitch;
  when big_cancel => loop a:=get_output;@/
                       exit when ((a<backup)and(a/=@' ')and
                            (a not in pspace..sspace))or(a>big_force);
                     end loop;
                     ignore_spaces:=FALSE;
                     goto reswitch;
  when pdollar | pspace..sspace =>
    @<Count the |pdollar| and space tokens; output the appropriate
      control sequences and |goto reswitch@;|@>;
  when indent..big_force => @<Output a \(control, look ahead in case of line 
                              breaks, possibly |goto reswitch|@>;
  when others => out1(a); {otherwise |a| is an ASCII character}
  end case;
  end loop;
end make_output;
 
@ Here we look ahead to see whether we have to output a begin-math control
sequence and/or a space control sequence

@<Count...@>=
d:=0; b:=0;
while (a=pdollar) or (a in pspace..sspace) loop
  if a=pdollar then
    incr(d);
  else
    b:=b+a-pspace+1;
  end if;
  a:=get_output;
  if cur_mode=inner then
    while a in big_cancel..backup loop
      if a=opt then
        a:=get_output; {|opt| is followed by digit}
      end if;
      a:=get_output;
    end loop;
  end if;
end loop;
if (d mod 2)=1 then
   out2(@'\')(@'?');
@.\\?@>
end if;
if not ignore_spaces and b>1 then
   out2(@'\')(@'8');
@.\\8@>
end if;
ignore_spaces:=FALSE;
goto reswitch@;

@ An identifier of length one does not have to be enclosed in braces, and it
looks slightly better if set in a math-italic font instead of a (slightly
narrower) text-italic font. Thus we output `\.{\\\char'174a}' but
`\.{\\\\\{aa\}}'.
 
@<Output an identifier@>=
out1(@'\');
if a=identifier then
  if ilk(cur_name)=predefined then
    out1(@'p');
@.\\p@>
  elsif length(cur_name)=1 then out1(@'|');
@.\\|@>
  else out1(@'\');
@.\\\\@>
  end if;
else out1(@'&'); {|a=res_word|}
@.\\\&@>
end if;
if length(cur_name)=1 then out1(byte_mem(cur_name mod ww,byte_start(cur_name)));
else out_name(cur_name);
end if@;
 
@ @<Output a \....@>=
out5(@'\')(@'m')(@'a')(@'t')(@'h');
if a=math_bin then out3(@'b')(@'i')(@'n');
elsif a=math_rel then out3(@'r')(@'e')(@'l');
else out2(@'o')(@'p');
end if;
@.\\mathbin@>
@.\\mathrel@>
@.\\mathop@>
out1(@'{')@;
 
@ The current mode does not affect the behavior of \.{AWEAVE}'s output routine
except when we are outputting control tokens.
 
@<Output a \(control...@>=
if a<break_space then
  if cur_mode=outer then
    out2(@'\')(a-cancel+@'0');
@.\\1@>
@.\\2@>
@.\\3@>
@.\\4@>
@.\\5@>
@.\\6@>
@.\\7@>
    if a=opt then out1(get_output); {|opt| is followed by a digit}
    end if;
  elsif a=opt then b:=get_output; {ignore digit following |opt|}
  end if;
else @<Look ahead for strongest line break, |goto reswitch|@>;
end if@;
 
@ If several of the tokens |break_space|, |force|, |big_force| occur in a
row, possibly mixed with blank spaces (which are ignored),
the largest one is used. A line break also occurs in the output file,
except at the very end of the translation. The very first line break
is suppressed (i.e., a line break that follows `\.{\\Y\\P}').
 
@<Look ahead for st...@>=
b:=a; save_mode:=cur_mode;
loop a:=get_output;
  if (a=cancel)or(a=big_cancel) then goto reswitch;
    {|cancel| overrides everything}
  end if;
  if ((a/=@' ')and(a<break_space)and(a not in pspace..sspace))or
      (a>big_force) then
    if save_mode=outer then
      if (out_ptr>3) and then 
         (out_buf(out_ptr-3..out_ptr)=(@'\',@'Y',@'\',@'P')) then 
        goto reswitch;
      end if;
@.\\P@>
@.\\Y@>
@.\\1@>
@.\\2@>
@.\\3@>
@.\\4@>
@.\\5@>
@.\\6@>
@.\\7@>
      out2(@'\')(b-cancel+@'0');
      ignore_spaces := b in force..big_force; 
      if a/=end_translation then finish_line; end if;
    elsif (a/=end_translation)and(cur_mode=inner) then out1(@' ');
    end if;
    goto reswitch;
  end if;
  if a>b then b:=a; end if; {if |a=@' '| we have |a<b|}
end loop@;
 
@ The remaining part of |make_output| is somewhat more complicated. When we
output a module name, we may need to enter the parsing and translation
routines, since the name may contain \ADA\ code embedded in
\ab\ constructions. This \ADA\ code is placed at the end of the active
input buffer and the translation process uses the end of the active
|tok_mem| area.
 
@<Output a module name@>=
out2(@'\')(@'X');
@.\\X@>
cur_xref:=xref(cur_name);
if num(cur_xref)>=def_flag then
  out_mod(num(cur_xref)-def_flag);
  if phase_three then
    cur_xref:=xlink(cur_xref);
    while num(cur_xref)>=def_flag loop
      out2(@',')(@' ');
      out_mod(num(cur_xref)-def_flag);
      cur_xref:=xlink(cur_xref);
      end loop;
    end if;
else out1(@'0'); {output the module number, or zero if it was undefined}
end if;
out1(@':'); @<Output the text of the module name@>;
out2(@'\')(@'X')@;
 
@ @<Output the text...@>=
k:=byte_start(cur_name); w:=cur_name mod ww; k_limit:=byte_start(cur_name+ww);
cur_mod_name:=cur_name;
while k<k_limit loop
  b:=byte_mem(w,k); incr(k);
  if b=@'@@' then @<Skip next character, give error if not `\.{@@}'@>;
  end if;
  if b/=@'|' then out1(b);
  else  @<Copy the \ADA\ text into |buffer(limit+1..j)|@>;
    save_loc:=loc; save_limit:=limit; loc:=limit+2; limit:=j+1;
    buffer(limit):=@'|'; output_ADA;
    loc:=save_loc; limit:=save_limit;
    end if;
  end loop@;
 
@ @<Skip next char...@>=
if byte_mem(w,k)/=@'@@' then
  print_nl("! Illegal control code in section name:");
@.Illegal control code...@>
  print_nl("<"); print_id(cur_mod_name); print("> "); mark_error;
  end if;
incr(k)@;
 
@ The \ADA\ text enclosed in \ab\ should not contain `\v' characters,
except within strings. We put a `\v' at the front of the buffer, so that an
error message that displays the whole buffer will look a little bit sensible.
The variable |string_delimiter| is zero outside of strings, otherwise it
equals the delimiter that began the string being copied.
 
@<Copy the \ADA\ text into...@>=
j:=limit+1; buffer(j):=@'|'; string_delimiter:=0;
loop  if k>=k_limit then
    print_nl("! ADA text in section name didn't end:");
@.ADA text...didn't end@>
    print_nl("<"); print_id(cur_mod_name); print("> "); mark_error;
    exit;
    end if;
  b:=byte_mem(w,k); incr(k);
  if b=@'@@' then @<Copy a control code into the buffer@>;
  else
    if b=@'"' then
      if string_delimiter=0 then string_delimiter:=b;
      elsif string_delimiter=b then string_delimiter:=0;
      end if;
    elsif (b=@''')and(byte_mem(w,k+1)=@''')and(string_delimiter=0) then
      j:=j+2; buffer(j-1..j):=(@''',byte_mem(w,k));
      k:=k+3; b:=@'''; 
    end if;
    if (b/=@'|')or(string_delimiter/=0) then
      if j>long_buf_size-3 then overflow("buffer");
      end if;
      incr(j); buffer(j):=b;
    else exit;
    end if;
  end if;
  end loop@;
 
@ @<Copy a control code into the buffer@>=
if j>long_buf_size-4 then overflow("buffer"); end if;
buffer(j+1):=@'@@'; buffer(j+2):=byte_mem(w,k); j:=j+2; incr(k)@;
 
@* Phase two processing.
We have assembled enough pieces of the puzzle in order to be ready to specify
the processing in \.{AWEAVE}'s main pass over the source file. Phase two
is analogous to phase one, except that more work is involved because we must
actually output the \TeX\ material instead of merely looking at the
\.{AWEB} specifications.
 
@<Phase II: Read all the text again and translate it to \TeX\ form@>=
reset_input; print_nl("Writing the output file...");
module_count:=0;
copy_limbo;
finish_line; flush_buffer(0,FALSE); {insert a blank line, it looks nice}
while not input_has_ended loop @<Translate the \(current module@>;
end loop@;
 
@ The output file will contain the control sequence \.{\\Y} between non-null
sections of a module, e.g., between the \TeX\ and definition parts if both
are nonempty. This puts a little white space between the parts when they are
printed. However, we don't want \.{\\Y} to occur between two definitions
within a single module. The variables |out_line| or |out_ptr| will
change if a section is non-null, so the following macros `|save_position|'
and `|emit_space_if_needed|' are able to handle the situation:
 
@d save_position==save_line:=out_line; save_place:=out_ptr@;
@d emit_space_if_needed==if (save_line/=out_line)or(save_place/=out_ptr) then
  out2(@'\')(@'Y'); end if@;
@.\\Y@>
 
@<Types...@>=
@!save_line:INTEGER; {former value of |out_line|}
@!save_place:sixteen_bits; {former value of |out_ptr|}
 
@ @<Translate the \(current module@>=
incr(module_count);@/
@<Output the code for the beginning of a new module@>;
save_position;@/
@<Translate the \TeX\ part of the current module@>;
@<Translate the \(definition part of the current module@>;
@<Translate the \(\ADA\ part of the current module@>;
@<Show cross references to this module@>;
@<Output the code for the end of a module@>@;
 
@ Modules beginning with the \.{AWEB} control sequence `\.{@@\ }' start in the
output with the \TeX\ control sequence `\.{\\M}', followed by the module
number. Similarly, `\.{@@*}' modules lead to the control sequence `\.{\\N}'.
If this is a changed module, we put \.{*} just before the module number.
@.\AT!\ @> @.\AT!*@>
 
@<Output the code for the beginning...@>=
out1(@'\');
if buffer(loc-1)/=@'*' then out1(@'M');
@.\\M@>
else  out1(@'N'); print("*"); print_int(module_count,1);
@.\\N@>
  update_terminal; {print a progress report}
  end if;
out_mod(module_count); out2(@'.')(@' ')@;
 
@ In the \TeX\ part of a module, we simply copy the source text, except that
index entries are not copied and \ADA\ text within \ab\ is translated.
 
@<Translate the \T...@>=
loop next_control:=copy_TeX;
case next_control is
when @'|' => init_stack; output_ADA;
when @'@@' => out1(@'@@');
when TeX_string ! xref_roman..xref_reserved ! module_name =>
  loc:=loc-2; next_control:=get_next; {skip to \.{@@>}}
  if next_control=TeX_string then
    err_print("! TeX string should be in ADA text only");
@.TeX string should be...@>
  end if;
when begin_comment ! end_comment ! thin_space ! 
     math_break ! line_break ! big_line_break ! 
     no_line_break ! join !pseudo_semi =>
          err_print("! You can't do that in TeX text");
@.You can't do that...@>
when others => null;
end case;
exit when next_control>=format;
end loop@;
 
@ When we get to the following code we have |next_control>=format|, and
the token memory is in its initial empty state.
 
@<Translate the \(d...@>=
if next_control<=definition then {definition part non-empty}
  emit_space_if_needed; save_position;
  end if;
while next_control<=definition loop {|format| or |definition|}
  init_stack;
  if next_control=definition then @<Start a macro definition@>;
  else @<Start a format definition@>;
  end if;
  outer_parse; finish_ADA;
  end loop@;
 
@ The |finish_ADA| procedure outputs the translation of the current
scraps, preceded by the control sequence `\.{\\P}' and followed by the
control sequence `\.{\\par}'. It also restores the token and scrap
memories to their initial empty state.
 
A |force| token is appended to the current scraps before translation
takes place, so that the translation will normally end with \.{\\6} or
\.{\\7} (the \TeX\ macros for |force| and |big_force|). This \.{\\6} or
\.{\\7} is replaced by the concluding \.{\\par} or by \.{\\Y\\par}.
 
@<Procedures in |second...@>=
procedure @!finish_ADA is {finishes a definition or a \ADA\ part}
@!p:text_pointer; {translation of the scraps}
begin out2(@'\')(@'P'); app_tok(force); app_comment; p:=translate;
@.\\P@>
app(p+tok_flag); make_output; {output the list}
if (out_ptr>1) and then (out_buf(out_ptr-1)=@'\') then
@.\\6@>
@.\\7@>
@.\\Y@>
  if out_buf(out_ptr)=@'6' then out_ptr:=out_ptr-2;
  elsif out_buf(out_ptr)=@'7' then out_buf(out_ptr):=@'Y';
  end if;
end if;
out4(@'\')(@'p')(@'a')(@'r'); finish_line;
@.\\par@>
stat if text_ptr>max_txt_ptr then max_txt_ptr:=text_ptr;end if;
if tok_ptr>max_tok_ptr then max_tok_ptr:=tok_ptr;end if;
if scrap_ptr>max_scr_ptr then max_scr_ptr:=scrap_ptr;end if;
tats@;
tok_ptr:=1; text_ptr:=1; scrap_ptr:=0; {forget the tokens and the scraps}
end finish_ADA;
 
@ @<Start a macro...@>=
sc5(pdollar)(backup)(@'\')(@'D')(pdollar)(math); {this will produce `\&{define }'}
@.\\D@>
next_control:=get_next;
if next_control/=identifier then err_print("! Improper macro definition");
@.Improper macro definition@>
else sc3(pdollar)(id_flag+id_lookup(normal))(pdollar)(math);
end if;
next_control:=get_next@;
 
@ @<Start a format...@>=
sc5(pdollar)(backup)(@'\')(@'F')(pdollar)(math); {this will produce `\&{format }'}
@.\\F@>
next_control:=get_next;
if next_control=identifier then
  sc3(pdollar)(id_flag+id_lookup(normal))(pdollar)(math);
  next_control:=get_next;
  if next_control=equivalence_sign then
    sc2(@'\')(@'S')(math); {output an equivalence sign}
@.\\S@>
    next_control:=get_next;
    if next_control=identifier then
      sc3(pdollar)(id_flag+id_lookup(normal))(pdollar)(math);
      sc0(semi); {insert an invisible semicolon}
      next_control:=get_next;
      end if;
    end if;
  end if;
if scrap_ptr/=5 then err_print("! Improper format definition");
@.Improper format definition@>
end if@;
 
@ Finally, when the \TeX\ and definition parts have been treated, we have
|next_control>=begin_ada|. We will make the global variable |this_module|
point to the current module name, if it has a name.
 
@<Types...@>=@!this_module:name_pointer; {the current module name, or zero}
 
@ @<Translate the \(\A...@>=
this_module:=0;
if next_control<=module_name then
  emit_space_if_needed; init_stack;
  if next_control=begin_ada then next_control:=get_next;
  else  this_module:=cur_module;@/
    @<Check that |=| or |==| follows this module name, and
      emit the scraps to start the module definition@>;
    end if;
  while next_control<=module_name loop
    outer_parse;@/
    @<Emit the scrap for a module name if present@>;
    end loop;
  finish_ADA;
  end if@;
 
@ @<Check that |=|...@>=
loop next_control:=get_next;@/
exit when next_control/=@'+'; {allow optional `\.{+=}'}
@.+=@>
end loop;
if (next_control/=@'=')and(next_control/=equivalence_sign) then
  err_print("! You need an = sign after the section name");
@.You need an = sign...@>
else next_control:=get_next;
end if;
if (out_ptr>1) and then 
   (out_buf(out_ptr-1..out_ptr)=(@'\',@'Y')) then
@.\\Y@>
    app(backup); {the module name will be flush left}
  end if;
sc1(mod_flag+this_module)(mod_scrap);
cur_xref:=xref(this_module);
if num(cur_xref)/=module_count+def_flag then
  sc3(math_rel)(@'+')(@'}')(math);
    {module name is multiply defined}
  this_module:=0; {so we won't give cross-reference info here}
  end if;
sc2(@'\')(@'S')(math); {output an equivalence sign}
@.\\S@>
sc1(force)(semi)@; {this forces a line break unless `\.{@@+}' follows}
@.\AT!+@>
 
@ @<Emit the scrap...@>=
if next_control<module_name then
  err_print("! You can't do that in ADA text");@/
@.You can't do that...@>
  next_control:=get_next;
elsif next_control=module_name then
  sc1(mod_flag+cur_module)(mod_scrap); next_control:=get_next;
end if@;
 
@ Cross references relating to a named module are given after the module ends.
 
@<Show cross...@>=
if this_module>0 then
  @<Rearrange the list pointed to by |cur_xref|@>;
  footnote(def_flag); footnote(0);
  end if@;
 
@ To rearrange the order of the linked list of cross references, we need
four more variables that point to cross reference entries.  We'll end up
with a list pointed to by |cur_xref|.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!next_xref,@!this_xref,@!first_xref,@!mid_xref:xref_number;
  {pointer variables for rearranging a list}
 
@ We want to rearrange the cross reference list so that all the entries with
|def_flag| come first, in ascending order; then come all the other
entries, in ascending order.  There may be no entries in either one or both
of these categories.
 
@<Rearrange the list...@>=
first_xref:=xref(this_module);
this_xref:=xlink(first_xref); {bypass current module number}
if num(this_xref)>def_flag then
  mid_xref:=this_xref; cur_xref:=0; {this value doesn't matter}
  loop  next_xref:=xlink(this_xref); xlink(this_xref):=cur_xref;
    cur_xref:=this_xref; this_xref:=next_xref;@/
    exit when num(this_xref)<=def_flag;
  end loop;
  xlink(first_xref):=cur_xref;
else mid_xref:=0; {first list null}
end if;
cur_xref:=0;
while this_xref/=0 loop
  next_xref:=xlink(this_xref); xlink(this_xref):=cur_xref;
  cur_xref:=this_xref; this_xref:=next_xref;
  end loop;
if mid_xref>0 then xlink(mid_xref):=cur_xref;
else xlink(first_xref):=cur_xref;
end if;
cur_xref:=xlink(first_xref)
 
@ The |footnote| procedure gives cross reference information about
multiply defined module names (if the |flag| parameter is |def_flag|), or about
the uses of a module name (if the |flag| parameter is zero). It assumes that
|cur_xref| points to the first cross-reference entry of interest, and it
leaves |cur_xref| pointing to the first element not printed.  Typical outputs:
`\.{\\A\ section 101.}'; `\.{\\U\ sections 370 and 1009.}';
`\.{\\U\ section 227(2)}';
`\.{\\A\ sections 8, 27\\*, and 64.}'.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |sec...@>=
procedure footnote(flag:sixteen_bits);

@ @<Procedures in |second...@>=
procedure @!footnote(@!flag:sixteen_bits) is {outputs module cross-references}
@!count:INTEGER; {counts the number of occurences of a cross-reference}
begin if num(cur_xref)<=flag then return; end if;
finish_line; out1(@'\');
@.\\A@>
@.\\U@>
if flag=0 then out1(@'U');
else out1(@'A');
end if;
out4(@' ')(@'s')(@'e')(@'c'); out4(@'t')(@'i')(@'o')(@'n');
@<Output all the module numbers on the reference list |cur_xref|@>;
out1(@'.');
end footnote;
 
@ The following code distinguishes three cases, according as the number
of cross references is one, two, or more than two.

@d count_xref==count:=1; loop exit when (num(xlink(cur_xref))<=flag) or @|
      (num(xlink(cur_xref))/=num(cur_xref));
      cur_xref:=xlink(cur_xref); incr(count); end loop@;

@<Output all the module numbers...@>=
count_xref;
first_xref:=xlink(cur_xref); {|first_xref| is the first entry of the second xref}
if num(first_xref)>flag then out1(@'s'); {plural}
end if;
out1(@'~');
loop  out_mod(num(cur_xref)-flag,count);
  cur_xref:=xlink(cur_xref); {point to the next cross reference to output}
  exit when num(cur_xref)<=flag;
  next_xref:=cur_xref; {save |cur_xref| before counting}
  count_xref;
  if (num(xlink(cur_xref))>flag)or(next_xref/=first_xref) then out1(@',');
    {not the last of two}
  end if;
  out1(@' ');
  if num(xlink(cur_xref))<=flag then out4(@'a')(@'n')(@'d')(@'~'); {the last}
  end if;
  end loop@;
 
@ @<Output the code for the end of a module@>=
out3(@'\')(@'f')(@'i'); finish_line;
flush_buffer(0,FALSE)@; {insert a blank line, it looks nice}
@.\\fi@>
 
@* Phase three processing.
We are nearly finished! \.{AWEAVE}'s only remaining task is to write out the
index, after sorting the identifiers and index entries.
 
@<Phase III: Output the cross-reference index@>=
phase_three:=TRUE; print_nl("Writing the index...");
if change_exists then
  finish_line; @/@<Tell about changed modules@>;
  end if;
finish_line; out4(@'\')(@'i')(@'n')(@'x'); finish_line;
@.\\inx@>
@/@<Do the first pass of sorting@>;
@<Sort and output the index@>;
out4(@'\')(@'f')(@'i')(@'n'); finish_line;
@.\\fin@>
@/@<Output all the module names@>;
out4(@'\')(@'c')(@'o')(@'n'); finish_line;
@.\\con@>
print("Done.")@;
@.Done.@>
 
@ Just before the index comes a list of all the changed modules, including
the index module itself.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!k_module:module_index; {runs through the modules}
 
@ @<Tell about changed modules@>=
k_module:=1;
while not changed_module(k_module) loop incr(k_module); end loop;
out4(@'\')(@'c')(@'h')(@' ');
@.\\ch@>
out_mod(k_module);
loop 
  loop incr(k_module);@/  
    exit when changed_module(k_module); 
  end loop;
  out2(@',')(@' '); out_mod(k_module);@/
  exit when k_module=module_count;
end loop;
out1(@'.')@;
 
@ A left-to-right radix sorting method is used, since this makes it easy to
adjust the collating sequence and since the running time will be at worst
proportional to the total length of all entries in the index. We put the
identifiers into 102 different lists based on their first characters.
(Uppercase letters are put into the same list as the corresponding lowercase
letters, since we want to have `$t<\\{TeX}<\&{then}$'.) The
list for character |c| begins at location |bucket(c)| and continues through
the |blink| array.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!bucket:array(ASCII_code) of name_pointer;
@!next_name: name_pointer; {successor of |cur_name| when sorting}
@!blink:name_info; {links in the buckets}
@!c:ASCII_code; {index into bucket}
 
@ To begin the sorting, we go through all the hash lists and put each entry
having a nonempty cross-reference list into the proper bucket.
 
@<Do the first pass...@>=
for d in INTEGER range 0..127 loop bucket(d):=0; end loop;
for h in INTEGER range 0..hash_size-1 loop
  next_name:=hash(h);
  while next_name/=0 loop
    cur_name:=next_name; next_name:=link(cur_name);
    if xref(cur_name)/=0 then
      c:=byte_mem(cur_name mod ww,byte_start(cur_name));
      if (c<=@'Z')and(c>=@'A') then c:=c+8#40#; end if;
      blink(cur_name):=bucket(c); bucket(c):=cur_name;
      end if;
    end loop;
  end loop@;
 
@ During the sorting phase we shall use the |cat| and |trans| arrays from
\.{AWEAVE}'s parsing algorithm and rename them |depth| and |head|. They now
represent a stack of identifier lists for all the index entries that have
not yet been output. The variable |sort_ptr| tells how many such lists are
present; the lists are output in reverse order (first |sort_ptr|, then
|sort_ptr-1|, etc.). The |j|th list starts at |head(j)|, and if the first
|k| characters of all entries on this list are known to be equal we have
|depth(j)=k|.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!depth: cat_type renames cat; 
                       {reclaims memory that is no longer needed for parsing}
@!head: trans_type renames trans; {ditto}
@!sort_ptr: scrap_index renames scrap_ptr; {ditto}
@!max_sorts: constant:=max_scraps; {ditto}
@#
@!cur_depth:eight_bits; {depth of current buckets}
@!cur_byte:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
@!cur_bank:w_range; {row of |byte_mem|}
@!cur_val:sixteen_bits; {current cross reference number}
stat@!max_sort_ptr:INTEGER range 0..max_sorts:=0; tats@; 
      {largest value of |sort_ptr|}
 
@ The desired alphabetic order is specified by the |collate| array; namely,
|collate(0)<collate(1)<@t$\cdots$@><collate(100)|.
 
@<Types...@>=@!collate:array(0..100) of ASCII_code; {collation order}
 
@ We use the order $\hbox{null}<\.\ <\hbox{other characters}<\.\_<
\.A=\.a<\cdots<\.Z=\.z<\.0<\cdots<\.9.$
 
@<Set init...@>=
collate(0):=0; collate(1):=@' ';
for d in INTEGER range 1..@' '-1 loop collate(d+1):=d; end loop;
for d in INTEGER range @' '+1..@'0'-1 loop collate(d):=d; end loop;
for d in INTEGER range @'9'+1..@'A'-1 loop collate(d-10):=d; end loop;
for d in INTEGER range @'Z'+1..@'_'-1 loop collate(d-36):=d; end loop;
collate(@'_'-36):=@'_'+1;
for d in INTEGER range @'z'+1..126 loop collate(d-63):=d; end loop;
collate(64):=@'_';
for d in INTEGER range @'a'..@'z' loop collate(d-@'a'+65):=d; end loop;
for d in INTEGER range @'0'..@'9' loop collate(d-@'0'+91):=d; end loop;
 
@ Procedure |unbucket| goes through the buckets and adds nonempty lists
to the stack, using the collating sequence specified in the |collate| array.
The parameter to |unbucket| tells the current depth in the buckets.
Any two sequences that agree in their first 255 character positions are
regarded as identical.

@<Types...@>= 
@!infinity: constant eight_bits:=255; {$\infty$ (approximately)}
 
@ @<Procedures in |third...@>=
procedure @!unbucket(@!d:eight_bits)is {empties buckets having depth |d|}
begin 
  for f in reverse 0..100 loop
  if bucket(collate(f))>0 then
    if sort_ptr>max_sorts then overflow("sorting");
    end if;
    incr(sort_ptr);
    stat if sort_ptr>max_sort_ptr then max_sort_ptr:=sort_ptr;end if;tats@;
    if f=0 then depth(sort_ptr):=infinity; else depth(sort_ptr):=d;
    end if;
    head(sort_ptr):=bucket(collate(f)); bucket(collate(f)):=0;
  end if;
  end loop;
end unbucket;
 
@ @<Sort and output...@>=
sort_ptr:=0; unbucket(1);
while sort_ptr>0 loop
  cur_depth:=depth(sort_ptr);
  if (blink(head(sort_ptr))=0)or(cur_depth=infinity) then
    @<Output index entries for the list at |sort_ptr|@>;
  else @<Split the list at |sort_ptr| into further lists@>;
  end if;
end loop@;
 
@ @<Split the list...@>=
next_name:=head(sort_ptr);
loop cur_name:=next_name; next_name:=blink(cur_name);
  cur_byte:=byte_start(cur_name)+cur_depth; cur_bank:=cur_name mod ww;
  if cur_byte=byte_start(cur_name+ww) then c:=0; {we hit the end of the name}
  else  c:=byte_mem(cur_bank,cur_byte);
    if (c<=@'Z')and(c>=@'A') then c:=c+8#40#; end if;
  end if;
  blink(cur_name):=bucket(c); bucket(c):=cur_name;@/
  exit when next_name=0;
end loop;
decr(sort_ptr); unbucket(cur_depth+1)@;
 
@ @<Output index...@>=
cur_name:=head(sort_ptr);
loop out2(@'\')(@':');@/
@.\\:@>
  @<Output the name at |cur_name|@>;
  @<Output the cross-references at |cur_name|@>;
  cur_name:=blink(cur_name);@/
  exit when cur_name=0;
end loop;
decr(sort_ptr)@;
 
@ @<Output the name...@>=
case ilk(cur_name) is
when normal => if length(cur_name)=1 then 
                 out2(@'\')(@'|'); 
               else 
                 out2(@'\')(@'\');
               end if;
@.\\|@>
@.\\\\@>
when roman => @+null;
when wildcard => @+out2(@'\')(@'9');
@.\\9@>
when italic => @+out2(@'\')(@'\');
when slanted => @+out2(@'\')(@'s');
@.\\s@>
when predefined => @+out2(@'\')(@'p');
@.\\p@>
when typewriter => @+out2(@'\')(@'.');
@.\\.@>
when others => @+out2(@'\')(@'&'); {|bold_face| or reserved word}
@.\\\&@>
end case;
out_name(cur_name)@;
 
@ Section numbers that are to be underlined are enclosed in
`\.{\\[}$\,\ldots\,$\.]', wheras those to be output in italics are
enclosed in `\.{\\\\\{}$\,\ldots\,$\.\}'. Here we have to consider a
special case: if section numbers $s_1,\ldots,s_n$ have to be output
and there are indices $1\leq i<j\leq n$ such that
$s_i+1=s_{i+1},s_{i+1}+1=s_{i+2},\ldots,s_{j-1}+1=s_j$ and $j=n$ or
$s_j+1\not=s_{j+1}$, we output `$s_i$\.{--}$s_j$'.
 
@<Output the cross-references...@>=
@<Invert the cross-reference list at |cur_name|, making |cur_xref| the head@>;
while cur_xref/=0 loop 
  out2(@',')(@' '); cur_val:=num(cur_xref); this_xref:=cur_xref;
  if cur_val<def_flag then
    next_xref:=xlink(this_xref);
    while (next_xref/=0) and then
          ((num(next_xref)<def_flag)and @|
           (num(this_xref)=(num(next_xref)-1))) loop
      this_xref:=next_xref;
      next_xref:=xlink(this_xref);
    end loop;
    out_mod(cur_val);
    if cur_xref/=this_xref then
      out2(@'-')(@'-');
@.--@>
      out_mod(num(this_xref));
    end if;
  elsif cur_val<body_flag then 
    out2(@'\')(@'['); out_mod(cur_val-def_flag); out1(@']');
  else
    out3(@'\')(@'\')(@'{'); out_mod(cur_val-body_flag); out1(@'}');
  end if;
@.\\[@>
@.\\\\@>
  cur_xref:=xlink(this_xref);
end loop;
out1(@'.'); finish_line@;
@..@>
 
@ List inversion is best thought of as popping elements off one stack and
pushing them onto another. In this case |cur_xref| will be the head of
the stack that we push things onto.
 
@<Invert the cross-reference list at |cur_name|, making |cur_xref| the head@>=
this_xref:=xref(cur_name); cur_xref:=0;
loop next_xref:=xlink(this_xref); xlink(this_xref):=cur_xref;
cur_xref:=this_xref; this_xref:=next_xref;@/
exit when this_xref=0;
end loop@;
 
@ The following recursive procedure walks through the tree of module names and
prints them.
@^recursion@>

@<Specification of procedures visible from |third...@>=
procedure mod_print(p:name_pointer);

@ @<Procedures in |third...@>=
procedure @!mod_print(p:name_pointer)is {print all module names in subtree |p|}
begin if p>0 then
  mod_print(llink(p));@/
  out2(@'\')(@':');@/
@.\\:@>
  tok_ptr:=1; text_ptr:=1; scrap_ptr:=0; init_stack;
  app(p+mod_flag); make_output;
  footnote(0); {|cur_xref| was set by |make_output|}
  finish_line;@/
  mod_print(rlink(p));
  end if;
end mod_print;
 
@ @<Output all the module names@>=@+mod_print(root)@;
 
@* The main program.
Let's put it all together now: \.{AWEAVE} starts and ends here.
@^system dependencies@>
 
The main procedure has been split into three sub-procedures in order to
keep certain \ADA\ compilers from overflowing their capacity.
@^split procedures@>

@<Specification of procedures visible from |first...@>=
procedure Phase_I;

@ @<Procedures in |first...@>=
procedure @!Phase_I is
begin @<Phase I:...@>;
end Phase_I;

@ @<Specification of procedures visible from |sec...@>=
procedure Phase_II;

@ @<Procedures in |second...@>=
procedure @!Phase_II is
begin @<Phase II:...@>;
end Phase_II;

@ @<Specification of procedures visible from |third...@>=
procedure Phase_III;

@ @<Procedures in |third...@>=
procedure @!Phase_III is
begin
  @<Phase III:...@>;
end Phase_III;

@
@d aweb_input_file_name=="input.web"
@d change_input_file_name=="input.ch"
@d TeX_output_file_name=="aweb_output.tex"
@.input.web@> @.input.ch@> @.aweb_output.tex@>

@<Types...@>=
@!opened:BOOLEAN:=FALSE;


@
@a
@~aweave.a@>
@.aweave.a@>
with Ada.Command_Line; use Ada.Command_Line;
with Ustrings; use Ustrings;
with TEXT_IO,int_number_io;
with data_structures,searching,input_output,first_phase,second_phase,third_phase;
use data_structures,searching,input_output,first_phase,second_phase,third_phase;
with Ada.Strings.Unbounded; use Ada.Strings.Unbounded;
procedure @!AWEAVE is
 ac : INTEGER := 0;
 ic : INTEGER := 0;
 yr_output_file : Ustring;
 begin
  print_ln("Trying to open input file.");
  ac := Argument_Count;
  if ac < 1 then
    fatal_error("No file on command line");
  end if;
  open_a_file(aweb_file,TEXT_IO.IN_FILE,Argument(1),opened);
  if not opened then
    fatal_error("AWEB file not open");
@.AWEB file not open@>
  end if;
  opened := FALSE;
  if ac >=2 then
    open_a_file(change_file,TEXT_IO.IN_FILE,Argument(2),opened);
  end if;
  if not opened then
    new_ln; print_ln("! No change file.");
@.No change file@>
  end if;
  ic := Index(U(Argument(1)),".");
  if ic = 0 then
    yr_output_file := U(Argument(1)) & ".tex";
  else
    yr_output_file := U(Argument(1));
    Overwrite(yr_output_file,ic,".tex");
    Ada.Strings.Unbounded.head(yr_output_file,ic+3);
  end if;
--  open_a_file(TeX_file,TEXT_IO.OUT_FILE,TeX_output_file_name,opened);
  open_a_file(TeX_file,TEXT_IO.OUT_FILE,
		S(yr_output_file),opened);
  if (not opened) and then
     (not create_TeX_file(S(yr_output_file))) then
    fatal_error("TeX file not open");
@.TeX file not open@>
  end if;
initialize;
print_ln(banner); {print a ``banner line''}
@<Store all the reserved words@>;
@<Store all the predefined identifiers@>;
Phase_I; Phase_II; Phase_III;@/
@<Check that all changes have been read@>;
raise end_of_AWEAVE;
exception
  when end_of_AWEAVE =>
  stat @<Print statistics about memory usage@>; tats@;
@t\4\4@>{here files should be closed if the operating system requires it}@;
@/@<Print the job |history|@>;
return;@t\2@>@;
end AWEAVE;
 
@ @<Print statistics about memory usage@>=
print_nl("Memory usage statistics: ");
print_int(name_ptr,1); print(" names, "); print_int(xref_ptr,1);
print(" cross references, ");
print_int(byte_ptr(0),1);
for i in 1..ww-1 loop print("+"); print_int(byte_ptr(i),1);
end loop;
  print(" bytes;");
print_nl("parsing required "); print_int(max_scr_ptr,1); print(" scraps, ");
print_int(max_txt_ptr,1);
  print(" texts, "); print_int(max_tok_ptr,1); print(" tokens, ");
print_int(max_stack_ptr,1); print(" levels;");
print_nl("sorting required "); print_int(max_sort_ptr,1); print(" levels.")@;
 
@ Some implementations may wish to pass the |history| value to the
operating system so that it can be used to govern whether or not other
programs are started. Here we simply report the history to the user.
@^system dependencies@>
 
@<Print the job |history|@>=
case history is
when spotless => @+print_nl("(No errors were found.)");
when harmless_message => @+print_nl("(Did you see the warning message above?)");
when error_message => @+print_nl("(Pardon me, but I think I spotted something wrong.)");
when fatal_message => @+print_nl("(That was a fatal error, my friend.)");
end case; {there are no other cases}
new_ln@; 

@* System-dependent changes.
This module should be replaced, if necessary, by changes to the program
that are necessary to make \.{AWEAVE} work at a particular installation.
It is usually best to design your change file so that all changes to
previous modules preserve the module numbering; then everybody's version
will be consistent with the printed program. More extensive changes,
which introduce new modules, can be inserted here; then only the index
itself will get a new module number.
@^system dependencies@>
 
@* Index.
If you have read and understood the code for Phase III above, you know what
is in this index and how it got here. All modules in which an identifier is
used are listed with that identifier, except that reserved words are
indexed only when they appear in format definitions, and the appearances
of identifiers in module names are not indexed. Underlined entries
correspond to where the identifier was declared. Error messages, control
sequences put into the output, and a few
other things like ``recursion'' are indexed here too.

